{"title_page": "Michael Avenatti", "text_new": "{{short description|American attorney and entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Michael Avenatti\n|image        = Michael Avenatti.jpg\n|caption      = Avenatti in 2018\n|birth_name   = Michael John Avenatti\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1971|2|16}}\n|birth_place  = [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|criminal_status = Convicted, awaiting sentencing\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Christine Carlin (divorced)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/magazine/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-donald-trump-media.html|title=The Fast and Furious Michael Avenatti|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|date=July 10, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref><br/>{{marriage|Lisa Storie|2011|2017|end=div}}<ref name=\"Lisa\">{{cite magazine |magazine=Earn The Necklace |title=Michael Avenatti's Ex-Wife, Lisa Storie-Avenatti: Who Is the Ex-Wife of Stormy Daniels' Attorney? |first=Dontei |last=Wynter |date=March 26, 2018 |accessdate=August 28, 2018 |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/michael-avenattis-ex-wife-lisa-avenatti/ |location=[[Concord, Ontario|Concord]], Ontario}}</ref>\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Saint Louis University]]<br/>[[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[George Washington University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|occupation   = Attorney\n|years_active = 1992\u20132020\n|website      = {{URL|avenatti.com|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael John Avenatti''' (born February 16, 1971) is an American attorney and convicted felon, best known for his representation of adult-film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] in [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|her lawsuits]] against President [[Donald Trump]], and his conviction for attempting to extort millions of dollars from sports apparel company [[Nike,_Inc.|Nike]].<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite web |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |title=Disgraced lawyer Michael Avenatti found guilty in Nike extortion trial |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/disgraced-lawyer-michael-avenatti-found-guilty-in-nike-extortion-trial.html |website=CNBC | date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Avenatti has been found guilty on all counts in Nike extortion trial |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/14/us/michael-avenatti-verdict/index.html |website=CNN| last=Cooper|first=Aaron|last2=Simon|first2=Darran|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dienst |first1=Jonathan |title=Michael Avenatti Guilty on All Counts in Nike Extortion Trial |website=NBC New York |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/michael-avenatti-guilty-on-all-counts-in-nike-extortion-trial/2287069/ |date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> His firm has represented various celebrity defendants and has filed suits against [[Fortune 100]] companies.<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.superlawyers.com/california-southern/article/the-scourge-of-kpmg/2afc085d-5bb4-472a-bc5c-4a9ca16915ef.html|title=Michael J. Avenatti \u2013 California Lawyers \u2013 The Scourge of KPMG|publisher=Superlawyers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-kimberlyclark-lawsuit/kimberly-clark-faces-500-million-lawsuit-over-ebola-protection-gear-idUSKBN0IJ1VV20141030|title=Kimberly-Clark faces $500 million suit over Ebola protection gown|date=October 30, 2014|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> He has appeared on broadcast television as well as in print as a legal commentator and as a representative for prominent clients. He was also a race car driver, having participated in races in the United States and Europe.<ref name=\"driverdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/drivers/michael-avenatti/|title=Michael Avenatti \u2013 Racing career profile|publisher=Driver Database}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti represented adult-film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] in [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|her lawsuits]] against President [[Donald Trump]] in an attempt to void a [[non-disclosure agreement]] she had signed. Avenatti also represented Daniels in a related defamation suit against Trump.  Before [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court Justice]] [[Brett Kavanaugh]] was confirmed, Avenatti introduced a written declaration in September 2018 accusing Kavanaugh of spiking drinks at parties for the purpose of allowing girls to be gang raped when he was in high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/read-full-sworn-statement-from-brett-kavanaugh-accuser-julie-swetnick.html|title=Read the full sworn statement from Julie Swetnick, the third woman to accuse Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh of sexual misconduct|date=September 26, 2018|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The accuser later repudiated the declaration in an interview with [[NBC News]], claiming Avenatti had misrepresented her allegations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/woman-kavanaugh-declaration-claims-avenatti-twisted-words-2018-10|title=A witness to alleged misconduct by Kavanaugh says Michael Avenatti 'twisted my words,' and that she only 'skimmed' her sworn declaration|date=October 26, 2018|publisher=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions starting in March 2019, Avenatti was indicted in California and New York on multiple federal counts including tax evasion, extortion, fraud, and embezzlement. In June 2019, the [[State Bar of California]] filed a proceeding to \"involuntarily\" enroll Avenatti as an inactive attorney\u2014in effect, to suspend him from practicing law in California\u2014based on evidence that, according to the State Bar, could lead to Avenatti's [[disbarment]].<ref name = \"2019-06-05 CalBar Application\"/> Avenatti had denied all the charges. On February 14, 2020, Avenatti was convicted of all charges against him in the New York court. Avenatti is currently held in [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|New York\u2019s Metropolitan Correctional Center]] while he awaits sentencing for his extortion conviction in the New York case. He faces potentially more than 40 years in prison. On April 11,2020 a judge released Avenatti in fear he would contract the Corona Virus. However the same judge insists that Trump friend Roger Stone be jailed for lying to the FBI. Stone is of older age with a history of asthma putting him at grave risk of death if contracted in prison. Yet Avenatti a staunch democrat and anti-trumper is not at high risk due to his age and health was released from prison presenting a dramatic contrast of the subjective importance by the judge who is a known democrat and Avenatti for president supporter. \nr<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/cnn-darling-michael-avenatti-nike|title=Ex-CNN darling Michael Avenatti convicted of trying to extort Nike|website=FOX News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Stempel|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-avenatti-idUSKBN2082EB|title=Celebrity lawyer Michael Avenatti is found guilty in Nike extortion case|date=2020-02-14|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2020-02-14|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/Y1MwY|archive-date=2020-02-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn on February 16, 1971, in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], California, Avenatti spent his early childhood in [[Colorado]] and [[Utah]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/michael-avenatti-the-adrenaline-fueled-lawyer-taking-on-donald-trump/2018/03/25/3ef5cbdc-2e88-11e8-b0b0-f706877db618_story.html|title=Michael Avenatti, the adrenaline-fueled lawyer taking on President Trump|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Roig-Franzia|first=Manuel|date=March 25, 2018|access-date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> His father was a manager for [[Anheuser-Busch]].<ref name = Ball>{{cite news |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |last2=Abramson|first2=Alana|title=Michael Avenatti's Past Won't Stop Him From Running in 2020 |url=http://time.com/5434317/michael-avenatti/ |publisher=Time Magazine |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref> He moved with his family to [[Chesterfield, Missouri|Chesterfield]], Missouri, a suburb of [[St. Louis]], in 1982, where he attended [[Parkway Central High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/porn-star-stormy-daniels-lawyer-graduated-from-parkway-central/article_8ce4cfef-818e-58db-8250-a8f7d317effa.html|last=Holleman|first=Joe|title=Porn star Stormy Daniels' lawyer graduated from Parkway Central |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> After graduating in 1989, Avenatti attended [[Saint Louis University]] for one year before transferring to the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] in 1996. While in college, he worked as an opposition researcher for [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s political consulting firm.<ref name = Ball/>\n\nAvenatti was wait-listed for [[George Washington University Law School]] (GW) and attended its night school program,<ref>https://abc3340.com/news/nation-world/avenatti</ref> during which he worked with Professor [[Jonathan Turley]] on constitutional issues relating to the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act]] (FISA).<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/> In 2000, he graduated [[Order of the Coif]] and first in class with a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]]<ref>[http://time.com/5434317/michael-avenatti/ \" by Molly Ball and Alana Abramson, ''TIME'',  October 25, 2018. Retrieved June 6, 2019.]</ref><ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/>  In 2003, his ''alma mater'' established the Michael J. Avenatti Award for Excellence in Pre-Trial and Trial Advocacy, after Avenatti made five figure donations to the school. The annual award is given to the member of the graduating Juris Doctor class who demonstrates excellence in [[pre-trial]] and trial advocacy. Avenatti was awarded GW's Alumni Recognition Award, in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gwu.edu/~magazine/archive/2010_law_winter/dept_philanthropy.html|title=GW Magazine|publisher=George Washington University}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhile in college and later in law school, Avenatti worked at The Research Group, a political [[opposition research]] and media firm run by [[Rahm Emanuel]] (later [[White House Chief of Staff]] for President [[Barack Obama]], and [[Mayor of Chicago]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-1992/Rahm-Emanuel-during-the-Bill-Clinton-Years/|title=A Rahm for the Money|last=Jannot|first=Mark|date=August 3, 1992|website=Chicago Magazine|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-stormy-daniels-lawyer-michael-avenatti-20180326-story.html|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer saw 'soft underbelly of politics' while working for Rahm Emanuel|last=Roig-Franzia|first=Manuel|date=March 26, 2018|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Avenatti worked on over 150 Democratic and Republican campaigns in 42 states while studying at George Washington University.<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\" />\n\nAfter law school, Avenatti worked at [[O'Melveny & Myers]] in Los Angeles, California, alongside [[Daniel M. Petrocelli]], who previously represented the [[Ron Goldman]] family in its case against [[O.J. Simpson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5190480/ns/dateline_nbc-newsmakers/t/man-behind-simpson-guilty-verdict/#.WhI087Q-eqA|title=Man behind Simpson guilty verdict|date=June 14, 2004|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> He assisted Petrocelli on multiple legal matters, including the representation of singer [[Christina Aguilera]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/40609/christina-s-court-fight|title=Christina's Court Fight|last=Farache|first=Emily|date=October 18, 2000|website=E! Online|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> and litigation surrounding the movie ''[[K-19: The Widowmaker]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/41182/harrison-ford-sub-drama-draws-fire|title=Harrison Ford Sub Drama Draws Fire|last=Grossberg|first=Josh|date=February 17, 2001|website=E! Online|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/03/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-attorney-relishes-his-role-as-trump-nemesis|title=The President May Be Able to Fire Mueller, but He Can't Fire Me|last=Hagan|first=Joe|date=March 23, 2018|work=The Hive|access-date=June 12, 2018|publisher=Vanity Fair|language=en}}</ref> and worked extensively for [[Don Henley]] and [[Glenn Frey]] of the musical group [[the Eagles]], including in a suit brought by former bandmate [[Don Felder]] against the group and [[Irving Azoff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/dec/08/business/fi-eagles-8|title=Reborn Eagles Lose Peaceful, Easy Feeling|first=Jeff|last=Leeds|date=December 8, 2002|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=\"superlawyers.com\" />\n\nAvenatti later joined Greene Broillet & Wheeler, a Los Angeles [[boutique law firm]]. While there, he handled a number of high-profile cases, including a $10 million defamation case against [[Paris Hilton]] which was resolved amicably by the parties before going to trial,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/celebrity/paris-hilton-settles-10-million-defamation-suit/|title=Paris Hilton Settles $10 Million Defamation Suit|date=August 23, 2007|work=People}}</ref> settled an idea-theft lawsuit relating to the show ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]'' and against producers [[Mark Burnett]] and [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/confidential/stormy-daniels-lawyer-sued-trump-paris-hilton-article-1.3861088|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer has negotiated settlements with Donald Trump and Paris Hilton |last=Niemietz|first=Brian|date=March 7, 2018|work=New York Daily News|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and a $40 million embezzlement lawsuit involving [[KPMG]].<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114359862516210767|title=KPMG Settles Targus Audit Case|first=David|last=Reilly|date=March 29, 2006|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Avenatti formed the law firm Eagan Avenatti, LLP (formerly known as Eagan O'Malley & Avenatti, LLP) with offices in [[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]], Los Angeles and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], California. The firm launched many high-profile lawsuits including one over allegedly defective hospital gowns.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/60-minutes-investigates-medical-gear-sold-during-ebola-crisis/|title=60 Minutes investigates medical gear sold during Ebola crisis|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=May 1, 2016|website=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref>  He has since appeared on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' three times in connection with cases he has handled.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/final-resting-place-cemeteries-lack-oversight/3/|title=Final resting place: Cemeteries lack oversight|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=May 21, 2012|website=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/|title=Stormy Daniels describes her alleged affair with Donald Trump|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=March 28, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Avenatti has also served as lead counsel on a number of historically large cases, including an April 2017 $454 million verdict after a jury trial in Federal Court in Los Angeles in a fraud case against [[Kimberly-Clark]] and [[Halyard Health]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hospital-gowns-20170410-story.html|title=Hospital gowns didn't protect as promised, jury says in $454-million fraud verdict|date=April 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> later reduced to a $21.7 million verdict upon appeal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.law.com/therecorder/2018/04/11/stormy-daniels-lawyer-avenatti-fights-to-save-huge-punitive-award-against-kimberly-clark/?slreturn=20180403234724|title=Stormy Daniels Lawyer Avenatti Fights to Save Huge Punitive Award Against Kimberly-Clark {{!}} The Recorder|last=Greene|first=Jenna|date=April 11, 2018|work=The Recorder|access-date=May 4, 2018}}</ref> an $80.5 million class-action settlement against [[Service Corporation International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/los_angeles/127210/|title=Eden Memorial Park settles lawsuit in $80.5 million deal|work=Jewish Journal|first=Jared|last=Sichel|date=February 27, 2014}}</ref> and a $41 million jury verdict against KPMG.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.com/njlawjournal/almID/1202425263932/|title=KPMG Assessed $41 Million for Failing to Divulge Fraud Revealed in Audit|website=New Jersey Law Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Avenatti formed a company, Global Baristas, to buy [[Seattle]]-based [[Tully's Coffee]] out of [[bankrupt]]cy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/washington/articles/2018-03-09/report-tullys-coffee-closing-stores-due-to-lack-of-coffee|title=Report: Tully's Stores Run Out of Coffee as Rebranding Looms|website=Usnews.com|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref> Avenatti first formed a partnership with actor [[Patrick Dempsey]], but Dempsey later backed away from the venture after a short legal battle that resulted in a settlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/dempsey-walks-away-from-tullyrsquos-after-suing-partner/|title=Dempsey walks away from Tully's after suing partner|date=August 23, 2013|work=Seattle Times}}</ref> Since 2015, Global Baristas has been named in more than 50 lawsuits in state and federal courts for breach of contract, unpaid bills, and unpaid taxes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/before-stormy-daniels-her-attorney-faced-allegations-of-dubious-business-dealings/|title=Before Stormy Daniels, her attorney faced allegations of dubious business dealings at Tully's Coffee|last=Kamb|first=Lewis|date=April 7, 2018|work=Seattle Times|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Avenatti prevailed against the [[National Football League]] (NFL) following a jury trial in [[Dallas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2015/03/12/dallas-jury-awards-76000-to-super-bowl-seat-plaintiffs-finds-no-fraud-by-nfl|title=Dallas jury awards $76,000 to Super Bowl seat plaintiffs, finds no fraud by NFL|date=March 12, 2015|work=Dallas News|access-date=May 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He later pursued a class-action suit on behalf of fans who showed up for [[Super Bowl XLV]] with tickets that didn't correspond to actual seats but the courts in Texas declined to certify the class.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2016, Avenatti filed another class action lawsuit against the NFL, this time on behalf of ticket-holders to the annual [[Pro Football Hall of Fame Game|Hall of Fame Game]], which was cancelled a few hours before kickoff.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/09/hall-of-fame-non-game-lawsuit-appears-to-be-looming/|title=Hall of Fame Non-Game lawsuit appears to be looming|last=Florio|first=Mike|date=August 9, 2016|work=ProFootballTalk|access-date=May 10, 2018|publisher=NBC Sports|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/11/class-action-filed-in-ohio-over-hall-of-fame-non-game/|title=Class action filed in Ohio of Hall of Fame Non-Game|last=Florio|first=Mike|date=August 11, 2016|website=ProFootballTalk|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a Florida man named Gerald Tobin alleged Avenatti failed to pay him $28,700 for private investigatory work. As a result, Avenatti's firm was abruptly forced into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/01/politics/avenatti-bankruptcy-lawsuit-stormy/index.html|title=Exclusive: How a 'nobody' ex-con pushed Avenatti law firm into bankruptcy}}</ref> In various news reports, including work done by CNN, Tobin was found to be an ex-con with four decades of convictions and jail time and not a licensed investigator. Tobin's claim forced Avenatti to cancel a deposition in an unrelated lawsuit days later, raising the question of collusion between Avenatti and Tobin. The issue was resolved when the pair entered into a [[non-disclosure agreement]], and Avenatti paid Tobin the $28,700.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Avenatti's law firm was subjected to a $10 million judgment in U.S. bankruptcy court.<ref name = \"Finnegan\"/> Avenatti has also defaulted on a $440,000 judgment in back taxes, penalties, and interest that he was personally obligated to pay under another bankruptcy settlement. The U.S. Attorney's office asserted in court that a motion seeking payment would soon be filed against Avenatti.<ref name=\"Finnegan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-bankruptcy-20180522-story.html|title=Law firm of Stormy Daniels' attorney hit with $10-million judgment|last=Finnegan|first=Michael|date=May 22, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Eagan Avenatti had been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings and, in December 2017, had agreed to pay $4.8 million in unpaid fees to a former partner, $2 million in back taxes, and $1 million to other creditors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/1023444/judge-oks-eagan-avenatti-s-exit-from-ch-11|title=Judge OKs Eagan Avenatti's Exit From Ch. 11|last1=Bolado|first1=Carolina|publisher=Lexis Law 360|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, the former partner filed a motion in U.S. bankruptcy court asking for a lien on any and all legal fees Avenatti's firm might collect, up to $10 million, from clients in 54 cases including his representation of Stormy Daniels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lawyer moves to seize Stormy Daniels' crowdfunding cash in Avenatti spat |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-stormy-daniels-avenatti-20180613-story.html |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a few days after [[Michael Avenatti#Personal life|his arrest]] on suspicion of domestic violence, Avenatti's law firm was evicted from its office in Newport Beach after skipping $213,000 worth of rent payments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/avenattis-law-firm-evicted-from-california-offices-over-unpaid-213g-rent|title=Avenatti's law firm evicted from California offices over unpaid $213G rent|last1=Mikeleonis|first1=Lukas|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=November 17, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, a former client filed arbitration against Avenatti, alleging misuse of settlement funds Eagan Avenatti LLP had received in trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/former-client-accuses-michael-avenatti-of-operating-law-firm-like-a-ponzi-scheme|title=Former Client Accuses Michael Avenatti of Operating Law Firm Like a 'Ponzi Scheme'|author=Betsy Briquelet and Kate Woodruff|date=January 23, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2019 the California State Bar filed a 573 page petition to enroll Avenatti in involuntary inactive status pending the outcome of the criminal cases and the disciplinary action which will be filed against him. The primary basis for the action was Avenatti's alleged embezzlement of $1,600,000 in funds from client Greg Barela.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/04/politics/avenatti-california-bar/index.html|title=The California State Bar has taken the first step to disbar Michael Avenatti|last=Silverman|first=Hollie|date=June 4, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Racing===\nSince 2010, Avenatti has raced as a driver in approximately 33 sportscar races, including various [[American Le Mans Series]], [[FIA World Endurance Championship]], [[Porsche Supercup]] and [[United SportsCar Championship]] races in the United States and in Europe. These races have included the [[24 Hours of Daytona]], [[12 Hours of Sebring]], [[2012 Petit Le Mans]], and the [[Long Beach Grand Prix]].<ref name=\"driverdb.com\"/> Avenatti had been planning to race the [[2013 24 Hours of Le Mans]], but replaced himself with [[Patrick Long]] a few weeks before the event because scheduling conflicts had arisen with his other business interests.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://autoweek.com/article/alms/patrick-long-join-patrick-dempsey-and-dempseydel-piero-racing-le-mans |title=Patrick Long to Join Patrick Dempsey and Dempsey/Del Piero Racing for Le Mans |author=Staff |work=[[Autoweek]] |date=May 29, 2013 |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> At the [[2015 24 Hours of Le Mans]], Avenatti teamed up with Saudi Prince [[Abdulaziz bin Turki Al Saud]] and Polish driver [[Jakub Giermaziak|Jakub \"Kuba\" Giermaziak]] in the No. 66 JMW Motorsport [[Ferrari 458]] Italia. The team placed seventh in its class.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fiawec.com/en/driver/265 |title=FIA Driver Categorisation \u2013 Michael Avenatti |publisher=[[FIA World Endurance Championship]] |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportscar365.com/lemans/lemans24/avenatti-le-mans-lived-up-to-the-expectation-level-and-then-some/ |title=Avenatti: 'Le Mans Lived Up to the Expectation Level and Then Some' |date=June 16, 2015 |author=John Dagys |work=Sportscar 365 |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n; 24 Hours of Le Mans results\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! Laps\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>pos.|Class p8osition}}\n|-\n! [[2015 24 Hours of Le Mans|2015]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} JMW Motorsport\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|POL}} [[Kuba Giermaziak]]<br>{{flagicon|KSA}} [[Abdulaziz bin Turki Al Saud|Abdulaziz al Faisal]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Ferrari 458 Italia GT2]]\n| GTE<br>Am\n| 320\n| 36th\n| 7th\n|-\n|}\n\n===Stormy Daniels lawsuits===\n{{Main|Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal}}\n[[File:Stormy Daniels and Michael Avenatti in 2018.png|thumb|Stormy Daniels and Michael Avenatti in 2018]]\nIn March 2018, Avenatti filed a lawsuit on behalf of adult film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] seeking to invalidate [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump legal dispute|a 2016 non-disclosure agreement]] regarding an alleged affair with Donald Trump in 2006, claiming that Daniels had been payed off by Trump's lawyer [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] not to disclose information covered by the NDA. The [[non-disclosure agreement]] had been negotiated in the final days of the [[2016 U.S. Presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/03/06/business/06reuters-usa-trump-daniels.html|title=Stormy Daniels Sues Trump Over 'Hush Agreement'|last=Hay|first=Andrew|date=March 6, 2018|access-date=June 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042121/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/03/06/business/06reuters-usa-trump-daniels.html|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|agency=Reuters|website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/porn-star-stormy-daniels-sues-president-trump/2018/03/06/1ad8e60a-21a7-11e8-a589-763893265565_story.html|title=Porn actress Stormy Daniels sues Trump, says hush agreement is null because he didn't sign it|last1=Reinhard|first1=Beth|last2=Sellers|first2=Frances Stead|date=March 6, 2018|work=Washington Post|last3=Brown|first3=Emma}}{{subscription only}}</ref> Avenatti also represented Daniels in a related defamation suit against Trump. In October 2018, a federal judge dismissed the defamation lawsuit and ordered Daniels to pay Trump's legal fees. Avenatti said he would appeal that decision; Daniels later said that Avenatti had initiated the suit against her wishes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/judge-throws-out-stormy-danielss-lawsuit-against-trump/2018/10/15/402935e8-d0cc-11e8-b2d2-f397227b43f0_story.html|title=Judge throws out Stormy Daniels's defamation lawsuit against Trump|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/28/us/stormy-daniels-michael-avenatti.html|title=Stormy Daniels Says Michael Avenatti Filed Trump Defamation Suit Against Her Wishes|last=Stevens|first=Matt|date=November 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti was a frequent guest on talk shows and cable news programs to discuss the cases, logging 108 [[CNN]] and [[MSNBC]] appearances between March 7 and May 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/stormy-daniels-lawyer-michael-avenatti-ready-his-star-turn-n867771|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer Michael Avenatti is ready for his star turn|last=Atkinson|first=Claire|date=April 20, 2018|work=[[NBCNews.com]]|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Joe|first1=Concha|title=Michael Avenatti has appeared on CNN and MSNBC 108 times since March 7, says Free Beacon|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/387325-michael-avenatti-has-appeared-on-cnn-and-msnbc-108-times-since-march-7-says|accessdate=May 11, 2018|agency=The Hill}}</ref> He also gained a large following on [[Twitter]]; he ended his tweets about the case and other Trump-related matters with the Twitter [[hashtag]] \"#basta\"\u2013the Italian word for \"enough.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-stormy-trump-20180407-story.html|title=Trump meets his match: Stormy Daniels' combative lawyer Michael Avenatti|author1=Michael Finnegan|author2=Maura Dolan|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Avenatti released records showing multiple large payments, some from major corporations, into the bank account Cohen had used to pay Daniels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Avenatti claims Michael Cohen received payments from firm controlled by Russian oligarch|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-lawyer-claims-cohen-received-payments-from-russian-oligarchs-company/|accessdate=May 14, 2018|publisher=CBS News|date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> Cohen's lawyers subsequently argued that some of the transactions released by Avenatti involved a different Michael Cohen, but they did not dispute the larger deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-wrong-person-bank-records-novartis-att-919029|title=Stormy Daniels's Attorney Michael Avenatti Got the Wrong Michael Cohen in Bank Records|last=Edevane|first=Gillian|date=May 10, 2018|work=Newsweek|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> The US Treasury Department opened an investigation into how Avenatti gained information from Cohen's private bank records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/09/michael-cohen-treasury-inspectors-investigate-leak-bank-records/596686002/|title=Treasury investigates possible leak of bank records for Trump lawyer Michael Cohen|last=Korte|first=Gregory|date=May 9, 2018|work=USA Today|access-date=May 28, 2018|last2=Schouten|first2=Fredreka|language=en}}</ref> Avenatti had also filed a motion to join the federal investigation of Michael Cohen. The federal judge issued Avenatti \"a choice\" that if he wanted to join he would have to end what the judge called his \"publicity tour\" of TV appearances and tweets about the case.<ref name=\"TIME\">{{cite news |title=Stormy Daniels' Attorney Drops Motion to Represent Her in Michael Cohen Probe |url=http://time.com/5295578/michael-avenatti-dropped-stormy-daniels-case-end-publicity-tour/ |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |publisher=TIME}}</ref> Avenatti withdrew the motion, and appeared on MSNBC that same day.<ref name=\"TIME\"/>\n\nIn early March 2019 Daniels terminated her arrangement with Avenatti, replacing him with attorney Clark Brewster. Later that month when federal charges against Avenatti were announced, she said \"Knowing what I know now about Michael, I\u2019m saddened but not shocked regarding his arrest.\"<ref name = Mangan/>\n\n===Immigration===\nAvenatti provided a video to [[MSNBC]] which aired on the June 25, 2018, episode of ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', a \"secretly shot\" video of a child in the custody of immigration officials who was separated from her mother. The video was leaked by a former employee whom Avenatti represents.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Samuels |first1=Brett |title=Former migrant detention facility worker leaks footage from inside facility to MSNBC |url=http://thehill.com/latino/394095-former-migrant-detention-facility-worker-leaks-footage-from-inside-facility-to-msnbc |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref> The leaked video was part of the response to the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].\n\n===Julie Swetnick allegations===\n{{Main|Brett Kavanaugh Supreme Court nomination}}\n[[File:2018 09 26 letter by US Senate Judiciary Committee Democrats on affidavit of Julie Swetnick.png|thumb|U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee Democrats on affidavit of Julie Swetnick]]\nIn September 2018, as the nomination of [[Brett Kavanaugh]] to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] was being evaluated in the Senate, two women accused him of inappropriate sexual conduct while in high school or college. Avenatti then announced that he had a client who made additional allegations against Kavanaugh, as both a witness and a victim of his inappropriate behavior, and that she would soon come forward publicly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/24/politics/michael-avenatti-brett-kavanaugh-cnntv/index.html|title=Avenatti promises new Kavanaugh accuser to come forward in next 48 hours|last=Tatum|first=Sophie|date=September 25, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref> On September 25, the woman was publicly identified by Avenatti as Julie Swetnick, a resident of [[Washington, D.C.]] and a 1980 graduate of [[Gaithersburg High School]] in Maryland. Swetnick claimed in a sworn [[affidavit]], signed under penalty of perjury, that Kavanaugh, as a high school student in the early 1980s, drank excessively and engaged in physically aggressive behavior toward girls. She said he was present at parties where girls were drugged and gang raped and that he participated in those activities. Swetnick also claims that she was gang raped at a party where Kavanaugh was present, although he did not personally participate in the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelAvenatti/status/1044960428730843136/photo/1?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1044960428730843136&ref_url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/michael-avenatti-identifies-kavanaugh-accuser-as-julie-swetnick.html|title=Michael Avenatti on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=September 26, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name = new>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/michael-avenatti-identifies-kavanaugh-accuser-as-julie-swetnick.html|title=New Kavanaugh accuser Julie Swetnick details parties where girls allegedly were drugged and raped|last=Breuninger|first=Dan Mangan, Kevin|date=September 26, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> Kavanaugh retorted, \"I don't know who this is and this never happened.\" September 26 the Democrats on the Judiciary Committee sent a letter to Chairman Grassley requesting \"[i]n light of shocking new allegations detailed by Julie Swetnick\" that the vote be immediately canceled and that Grassley should support either the reopening of the FBI investigation or the withdrawal of Kavanaugh's nomination.<ref name = new/> In an NBC interview, Swetnick provided the names of four friends who went to the parties with her \u2013 however, one is deceased and another did not know her.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kavanaugh accuser Julie Swetnick speaks out on sexual abuse allegations |url=https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/other/kavanaugh-accuser-julie-swetnick-speaks-out-on-sexual-abuse-allegations/ar-BBNPJks |date=September 26, 2018|agency=NBC News}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti announced that he had a sworn declaration by another woman backing up Swetnick's accusations. Subsequently, NBC news reported that the unnamed declarant told them on September 30 (before Michael Avenatti released her sworn statement on October 3 with her name blacked out) that she never thought it was Kavanaugh spiking the punch, and that she never witnessed him act inappropriately towards girls. In a text to NBC News on October 4, the unnamed accuser reiterated, \"It is incorrect that I saw Brett spike the punch. I didn't see anyone spike the punch...I was very clear with Avenatti from day one,\" adding that she would never allow anyone to be abusive towards males or females in her presence. She also expressed that she had only given her sworn declaration a cursory look. The response to NBC news by Avenatti was that she read, signed and repeatedly stood behind the sworn declaration. The unnamed declarant contacted NBC news October 5 and reiterated her denial of ever seeing Kavanaugh spike punch or act inappropriately toward women, and charged Avenatti with twisting her words.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snow |first1=Kate |last2=Schecter |first2=Anna |title=New questions raised about Avenatti claims regarding Kavanaugh |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/new-questions-raised-about-avenatti-claims-regarding-kavanaugh-n924596 |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |publisher=National Broadcasting Company |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nKavanaugh was confirmed to the Supreme Court by a margin of 50-48, mostly along party lines. Several Democratic Senators blamed Avenatti as the Swetnick accusation \"gave Republicans an opportunity to shift the narrative away from Ford's allegations and make a broader case that the growing accusations of sexual misconduct amounted to an orchestrated Democratic smear campaign\". Senator [[Susan Collins]], a Republican swing vote, called the Swetnick allegation \"outlandish...[without] any credible supporting evidence\", and ended up supporting Kavanaugh's nomination. Senator [[Gary Peters]] said that Avenatti's allegations \"turns it into a circus atmosphere and certainly that's not where we should be\", while another Senate aide said that \"Democrats and the country would have been better off if Mr. Avenatti spent his time on his Iowa vanity project rather than meddling in Supreme Court fights\". Avenatti fired back, criticizing anonymous Democrats as \"cowards\", arguing that this showed \"failed leadership\" in the Democratic Party.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/06/politics/democrats-avenatti-swetnick-accusation/index.html Manu Raju, \"Democrats say Avenatti undercut their case against Kavanaugh\"], CNN Politics, October 8, 2018.</ref>\n\nSenate Judiciary Chairman [[Chuck Grassley]] referred Avenatti and Swetnick to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] for a possible criminal investigation over allegations they made false statements to Congress about now-Supreme Court Justice Brett Kavanaugh. Avenatti called the referral \"completely baseless.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/25/politics/julie-swetnick-justice-department-judiciary-committee/index.html|title=Judiciary chairman refers Swetnick, Avenatti to Justice Department|last=de Vogue|first=Ariane|date=October 25, 2018|website=CNN|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/413153-grassley-refers-swetnick-avenatti-to-justice-dept-for-investigation|title=Grassley refers Swetnick, Avenatti to Justice Dept. for investigation|last=Carney|first=Jordain|date=October 25, 2018|website=The Hill|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/grassley-refers-avenatti-and-swetnick-to-justice-for-a-criminal-probe/2018/10/25/75ef7a02-d879-11e8-9559-712cbf726d1c_story.html|title=Grassley refers Avenatti and Swetnick to Justice for a criminal probe|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|date=October 25, 2018|website=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Potential 2020 presidential campaign===\nAvenatti expressed interest in [[2020 United States presidential election|running for President of the United States in 2020]]; he started a [[political action committee]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/us/politics/michael-avenatti-president.html|title=Michael Avenatti, Stormy Daniels's Lawyer, Eyes Another Gig: President|access-date=August 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennifer Epstein |last2=John McCormick |title=Avenatti Says He's Serious About Running Against Trump in 2020 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-28/stormy-daniels-lawyer-says-he-s-serious-about-a-2020-campaign |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |work=Bloomberg |date=28 August 2018 |quote=Last week alone, Michael Avenatti hobnobbed with Democratic National Committee leaders in Chicago, started a political action committee to raise money for Democratic congressional candidates, and met with David Axelrod, former President Barack Obama\u2019s strategist.}}</ref> and held his first fundraiser at the Democratic Wing Ding in August.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maggie Astor |title=Michael Avenatti Urges Democrats to Reject Michelle Obama's Advice on Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/us/politics/michael-avenatti-michelle-obama-trump.html |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |work=The New York Times |issue=August 10, 2019 |quote=his keynote speech Friday night at the Democratic Wing Ding, a party fund-raiser in northern Iowa}}</ref> In September 2018, Avenatti said he would run in 2020 only against Trump or Pence.<ref>{{Citation|last=CBC News: The National|title=Lawyer for Stormy Daniels considers running for president|date=September 10, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_DpHHB6nAbw&t=9m53s|access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> On November 1, 2018, Avenatti released his first political ad, which urged Americans to vote on November 6, 2018;<ref name=\"POL-20181101\">{{cite news |last=Koreck |first=Natasha |title=Avenatti launches his first political ad - The attorney wouldn't say how much he's spending on the digital spot that will run on Facebook and Twitter. |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/11/01/avenatti-political-ad-953758 |date=November 1, 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 }}</ref> ''[[the Washington Post]]'' ranked him a top 15 contender.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aaron Blake |title=The top 15 Democratic presidential candidates for 2020, ranked |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/09/top-democratic-presidential-candidates-ranked/ |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=November 9, 2019 |quote=Democrats are starting to warm to his brash, in-your-face style}}</ref> On December 4, 2018, Avenatti announced that he would not be a candidate for president of the United States in 2020. In a Twitter post, he announced \"I do not make this decision lightly \u2014 I make it out of respect for my family.\"<ref name=\"notrun\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/04/michael-avenatti-announces-he-will-not-run-for-president-in-2020.html|title=Michael Avenatti announces he will not run for president in 2020|newspaper=CNBC|author=Dan Mangan|date=December 4, 2018|accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests and charges==\n===Domestic violence complaint===\nIn November 2018, Avenatti was arrested on suspicion of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=Michael Avenatti has reportedly been arrested for domestic violence |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/14/18095836/michael-avenatti-domestic-violence-arrest-stormy-daniels-2020-president |date=November 14, 2018 |website=Vox.com |publisher=Vox}}</ref> The [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) later confirmed Avenatti was arrested for felony domestic violence and his bail was set at $50,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=LA Police Department |url=https://twitter.com/LAPDHQ/status/1062876803587432448 |website=Official Twitter |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Avenatti arrested on suspicion of domestic violence: LAPD |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/michael-avenatti-arrested-on-suspicion-of-domestic-violence-lapd |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |agency=Fox News Corp.}}</ref> An LAPD spokesperson said that the unidentified victim, later described as his girlfriend,<ref name=\"Lee_11/21/2018\"/> had \"visible injuries\" and that the case would be referred to the [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]] for prosecution.<ref name = \"Croucher\"/> Minutes after the reports of Avenatti's arrest, the Twitter account of Surefire Intelligence, a company created by the [[far-right]] [[conspiracy theorist]] [[Jacob Wohl]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/15/michael-avenatti-arrested-suspicion-domestic-violence/|title=Michael Avenatti arrested on suspicion of domestic violence, calls allegations 'completely bogus'|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|date=November 15, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=February 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217083813/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/15/michael-avenatti-arrested-suspicion-domestic-violence/|archive-date=December 17, 2018|url-status=live|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Eli|last3=Paul|first3=Deanna|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"snopes_2018-11-16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2018/11/16/michael-avenatti-was-arrested-on-domestic-violence-charges-and-then-things-got-weird/|title=Michael Avenatti Was Arrested on Domestic Violence Charges, And Then Things Got Weird|last=Palma|first=Bethania|date=November 16, 2018|website=[[Snopes]]|language=en-US|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> seemingly claimed responsibility for the arrest, tweeting a news story about it and adding \"Surefire Intelligence strikes again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/if-surefire-intelligence-really-was-behind-false-avenatti-police-report-jacob-wohl-could-be-in-deep-trouble/|title=If Surefire Intelligence Really Was Behind False Avenatti Police Report, Jacob Wohl Could Be in Deep Trouble|last=Naham|first=Matt|date=November 15, 2018|website=[[Dan Abrams#Law & Crime|Law & Crime]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116010027/https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/if-surefire-intelligence-really-was-behind-false-avenatti-police-report-jacob-wohl-could-be-in-deep-trouble/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=November 15, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti called the allegations \"completely bogus\" and \"fabricated and meant to do harm to my reputation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/michael-avenatti-denies-alleged-domestic-violence-ive-never-been-physically-abusive-in-my-life/|title=Avenatti Denies 'Fabricated' Allegations of Domestic Violence: I've Never Been 'Physically Abusive in My Life'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Both of his ex-wives issued statements that Avenatti had never been violent toward either of them.<ref name = \"Croucher\"/> The county district attorney declined to press charges, and referred the case to the city attorney for possible misdemeanor charges.<ref name=\"Lee_11/21/2018\">{{cite web | last=Lee | first=Michelle Ye Hee | title=Los Angeles prosecutors decline to file felony domestic abuse charges against Michael Avenatti | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=November 21, 2018 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/los-angeles-prosecutors-decline-to-file-felony-domestic-abuse-charges-against-michael-avenatti/2018/11/21/c8ac3024-edd6-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html | access-date=November 22, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, the city attorney's office announced that their investigation was complete, and that Avenatti would not be charged.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stack |first=Liam |date=February 1, 2019 |title=Michael Avenatti Will Not Be Charged With Domestic Violence, Officials Say |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/01/us/michael-avenatti-domestic-violence.html |work=The New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\n===Extortion charge===\nOn March 25, 2019, Avenatti was arrested in New York City, and federal prosecutors in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] announced that they were charging Avenatti with attempting to [[Extortion|extort]] up to $25 million from U.S. athletic apparel and shoe company [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] by threatening to make damaging charges against the company.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/michael-avenatti-charged-nike-extortion-2019-3|title=Michael Avenatti charged for attempting to extort more than $20 million from Nike|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|website=Business Insider|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/michael-avenatti-accused-of-trying-to-extort-nike-for-up-to-25m-feds-say|title=Michael Avenatti accused of trying to extort Nike for up to $25M, feds say|last=Sang|first=Lucia Suarez|last2=Chamberlain|first2=Samuel|date=March 25, 2019|website=[[Fox News]]|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti allegedly claimed that Nike improperly made payments to families of high school basketball players.<ref>{{cite news |date=March 25, 2019 |title=5 of the Most Explosive Details From the Michael Avenatti-Nike Extortion Case |author=Sheena Butler-Young |publisher=Fairchild Publications |work=Footwear News |url=https://footwearnews.com/2019/business/legal-news/michael-avenatti-nike-extortion-scandal-details-allegations-1202764390/ |accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> The arrest came about 15 minutes after Avenatti announced that he would be holding a press conference the next day, at which he claimed he would reveal information about a high school and college basketball scandal involving Nike.<ref name=\"Mangan\" /> \n\nDuring the afternoon of March 25, Avenatti and an unnamed co-conspirator were scheduled to meet with lawyers from Nike, at which prosecutors allege he would have offered to cancel the press conference in exchange for payment.<ref name = Mangan>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/25/michael-avenatti-to-be-charged-with-wire-and-bank-fraud.html|title=Stormy Daniels' ex-lawyer Michael Avenatti arrested for alleged $20 million extortion scheme against Nike, embezzling client's money, defrauding bank|last1=Mangan|first1=Dan|last2=Breuninger|first2=Kevin|date=March 25, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti's suspected co-conspirator was identified as [[Mark Geragos]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Avenatti was released on a $300,000 bond that evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/michael-avenatti-charged/index.html|title=Lawyer Michael Avenatti charged: Live updates|date=March 25, 2019 |website=www.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 14, 2020, Avenatti was found guilty on all three counts related to the attempted extortion of Nike. He faces potentially more than 40 years in prison.<ref name=\"CNBC\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Fraud and embezzlement charges===\nAlso on March 25, 2019, the [[U.S. Attorney for the Central District of California]], [[Nicola T. Hanna]], announced in Los Angeles the filing of a 197-page complaint accusing Avenatti of [[wire fraud]] and [[bank fraud]].<ref name = Mangan/> The indictment said that Avenatti had [[embezzlement|embezzled]] money from a client and had defrauded a Mississippi bank by submitting false tax returns to obtain more than $4 million in loans. Prosecutors also alleged that Avenatti had not filed personal tax returns for the years in question.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawyer Michael Avenatti arrested, faces wire fraud and bank fraud charges|date=March 25, 2019|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2019, Avenatti was charged by a federal grand jury in [[Santa Ana, California]] of embezzling funds that his client, NBA player [[Hassan Whiteside]], had wired to him in January 2017 for the purpose of paying a settlement to his ex-girlfriend. Avenatti stands accused of withholding client funds and applying most of the settlement money of $1.75 million, along with his included $1 million fee, in order to invest $2.5 million in a share of a private jet. He is further accused of misrepresenting Whiteside\u2019s settlement payment as monthly installments, which he paid out until June 2018, totaling $194,000.  Federal agents subsequently seized a Honda HA-420 twin-engine jet from Santa Barbara Airport that was co-owned by Avenatti and former client, Indigo Systems co-founder William J. Parrish, as the latter was about to embark on a flight. Parrish successfully sued Avenatti in 2017 for $2.1 million for failure to repay a 2013 loan. Avenatti had not appeared in court to defend himself and is appealing that judgment. Avenatti denies the charges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Avenatti accused of embezzling nearly $2 million that NBA player paid ex-girlfriend |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-hassan-whiteside-embezzlement-20190421-story.html |publisher=LA Times}}</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/04/22/michael-avenattis-alleged-embezzlement-included-millions-heats-hassan-whiteside/ \"Michael Avenatti\u2019s alleged embezzlement included payment from Heat\u2019s Hassan Whiteside\", by Des Bieler, April 22, 2019. Retrieved April 22, 2019.]</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2019, 36 additional financial crime charges were announced by the U.S. Attorney for the Central District of California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/11/politics/michael-avenatti-indicted-los-angeles/index.html|title=Michael Avenatti indicted on 36 counts|last=Orden|first=Erica|website=CNN|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-avenatti/lawyer-avenatti-charged-in-california-with-u-s-fraud-tax-crimes-idUSKCN1RN23B \"Avenatti, lawyer known as Trump foe, indicted for financial crimes\", by Jonathan Allen, ''Reuters'', April 11, 2019. Retrieved April 11, 2019.]</ref> Avenatti is accused of stealing money from clients to purchase a $5 million private jet he co-owned, as well as fraud related to tax documents and banking information.<ref name=Bever11April>{{cite news|work=The Washington Post|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/04/11/michael-avenatti-hit-with-federal-charges-including-tax-fraud-embezzlement-report-says/ |title=Michael Avenatti charged with stealing millions from clients, using 'ill-gotten gains' for a private jet |first1=Lindsey|last1=Bever|first2=Devlin|last2=Barrett |first3=Mark |last3=Berman }}</ref> According to U.S. Attorney Hanna, \"[m]oney generated from one set of crimes was used to further other crimes, typically in the form of payments designed to string along victims.\" The purpose of his crimes was \"to prevent Mr. Avenatti\u2019s financial house of cards from collapsing.\"<ref name=Bever11April/> Vowing to \"fully fight\" the additional charges and appealing to the public to presume his innocence, Avenatti stated on Twitter that \"[f]or 20 years, I have represented Davids vs. Goliaths and relied on due process and our system of justice. Along the way, I have made many powerful enemies.\"<ref name=Bever11April/>\n\nOn May 22, 2019, Avenatti was charged with wire fraud and aggravated identity theft as a result of allegations that he stole money from former client [[Stormy Daniels]] while helping negotiate her 2018 book deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/22/politics/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-indictment/index.html|title=Michael Avenatti charged with stealing $300,000 from former client Stormy Daniels|last=Orden|first=Erica|date=May 22, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FraudChargesPBS\">{{cite web |title=Avenatti pleads not guilty to defrauding Stormy Daniels |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/avenatti-pleads-not-guilty-to-defrauding-stormy-daniels |publisher=PBS |accessdate=May 28, 2019 |date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti pleaded not guilty. Avenatti was released on a $300,000 bail bond on conditions that he notify authorities of any travel plans and that he have no contact with Daniels.<ref>[https://www.aol.com/article/news/2019/05/28/trump-foe-avenatti-pleads-not-guilty-to-ripping-off-stormy-daniels/23735913/ Brendan Pierson, \"Trump foe Avenatti pleads not guilty to ripping off Stormy Daniels\"], Reuters, 28 May 2019.</ref><ref name=\"FraudChargesPBS\"/>\n\n=== Disbarment proceeding in California ===\n\nOn June 5, 2019, the [[State Bar of California]] filed with the California State Bar Court a 573-page application, under [[California Codes|California Business and Professions Code]] section 6007(c)(2), to involuntarily enroll Avenatti as an inactive member of the bar.<ref name = \"2019-06-05 CalBar Application\">''Matter of Michael John Avenatti'', Case Number SBC-19-TE-30258,\n{{cite report\n|url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/courtDocs/19-TE-30259-2.pdf\n|title=Corrected Application for Involuntary Inactive Enrollment\n|docket = |date = June 5, 2019\n|publisher = [[State Bar of California]]}}</ref> The State Bar Court is the court that decides whether a California attorney committed professional misconduct worthy of discipline, up to and including disbarment. The State Bar contends that the evidence submitted with the petition establishes that Avenatti has committed professional misconduct that has caused or is causing substantial harm to Avenatti's clients or to the public and that there is a substantial probability that Avenatti's professional misconduct will result in his [[disbarment]]. If the State Bar Court finds sufficient evidence to place Avenatti on involuntary inactive enrollment, the State Bar must initiate disciplinary proceedings within 45 days of the effective date of the order. If the State Bar Court rules on disbarment, the California Supreme Court must review and approve it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rules of Procedure of the State Bar of California |url=https://www.calbar.ca.gov/Portals/0/documents/rules/Rules_Title5_Procedure.pdf |website=State Bar of California |accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===January 2020 arrest===\nAvenatti was again arrested on January 14, 2020 during a recess in court for his disbarment proceedings, for violating the terms of a previous release, and was expected to appear in federal court in [[Santa Ana, California]] on January 15.<ref name=\"db\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-avenatti-arrested-by-feds-at-california-state-bar-hearing|title=Michael Avenatti Arrested by Feds at California State Bar Hearing|work=The Daily Beast|date=January 15, 2020|accessdate=January 15, 2020|last=McGahan|first=Jason}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Avenatti was scheduled to face trial in New York on charges of attempting to extort millions from Nike when a federal judge in California ordered him jailed until his trial in California. Prosecutors in California accused Avenatti of violating the conditions of his release by committing a series of financial crimes while free on bond: [[structuring]] currency transactions to avoid reporting requirements and concealing his personal assets from his creditors. U.S. Marshals were prepared to take Avenatti to Manhattan as early as January 17, 2020 for his trial on the New York charges. Avenatti's trial on the California charges was scheduled for the following May. Michael Avenatti also faced additional New York charges of wire fraud, identity theft, and embezzling almost $300,000 from [[Stormy Daniels]], his former client.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-avenatti-faces-new-federal-charges-in-california-11579113731|title=Michael Avenatti Ordered Jailed Until Trial|last=Ramey|first=Corinne|last2=O'Brien|first2=Rebecca Davis|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:2015 Honda HA-420 HondaJet 42000029 by D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|2015 Honda HA-420 HondaJet N227WP co-owned by Avenatti]]\n\nAvenatti was married for 13 years to Christine Carlin Avenatti, with whom he has two teenage daughters.<ref name=\"Croucher\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/michael-avenatti-denies-domestic-abuse-allegation-i-did-not-strike-my-ex-wife-1216461|title=Michael Avenatti Denies Domestic Abuse Allegation|last=Croucher|first=Shane|date=November 15, 2018|work=Newsweek|accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> He married Lisa Storie in 2011. They have one son. Lisa Storie-Avenatti filed for divorce in December 2017.<ref name = Lisa/> In December 2018, according to court documents, Avenatti and his wife settled their divorce, with Avenatti agreeing to pay Lisa $1,947,540 in child and spousal support, and to transfer ownership of several assets to her, including five luxury wristwatches, a [[Frank Gehry]] sculpture, other artwork, and a leased 2017 [[Ferrari 488]] GT Spider, while his law firm would transfer to Lisa its interest in a 2015 Honda private jet.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Bill Bostock |title=Michael Avenatti reportedly will turn over cars, watches, and a jet to pay nearly $2 million to his estranged wife as part of their divorce agreement |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/avenatti-loses-thousands-in-lisa-storie-divorce-ferrari-watches-report-2018-12 |work=Business Insider |accessdate=May 23, 2019 |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe jet was later confiscated by federal agents at Santa Barbara Airport on April 10, 2019, during an asset seizure based on the tax, wire, and bankruptcy fraud indictment filed in the U.S. Central District Court of California.<ref>{{cite news |author1=William La Jeunesse |author2=Paulina Dedaj |title=Feds seize $4.5 million Avenatti plane amid tax scandal |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/feds-seize-4-5-million-avenatti-plane-amid-tax-scandal |accessdate=May 23, 2019 |work=Fox News |date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Michael Cohen (lawyer)#Essential Consultants LLC}}\n* {{section link|Michael Cohen (lawyer)#Payment to Stormy Daniels}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links|b=no|commons=Category:Michael Avenatti|d=Q43380465|n=no|q=Michael Avenatti|s=no|v=no|wikt=no|w=Michael Avenatti}}\n* {{Official}}\n* [https://www.dropbox.com/s/kiwkzgyzgztmrq1/WhatIBelieve.pdf Michael Avenatti \u2013 List of Political Beliefs (August 27, 2018)]\n* {{Racing-Reference driver|Michael_Avenatti}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Avenatti, Michael}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Sebring drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Daytona drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:American commentators]]\n[[Category:American extortionists]]\n[[Category:American Le Mans Series drivers]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:California lawyers]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump litigation]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with O'Melveny & Myers]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from California]]\n[[Category:Rolex Sports Car Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:WeatherTech SportsCar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American attorney and entrepreneur}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n|name         = Michael Avenatti\n|image        = Michael Avenatti.jpg\n|caption      = Avenatti in 2018\n|birth_name   = Michael John Avenatti\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1971|2|16}}\n|birth_place  = [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], [[California]], U.S.\n|death_date   =\n|death_place  =\n|criminal_status = Convicted, awaiting sentencing\n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Christine Carlin (divorced)<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/07/10/magazine/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-donald-trump-media.html|title=The Fast and Furious Michael Avenatti|last=Shaer|first=Matthew|date=July 10, 2018|work=The New York Times}}</ref><br/>{{marriage|Lisa Storie|2011|2017|end=div}}<ref name=\"Lisa\">{{cite magazine |magazine=Earn The Necklace |title=Michael Avenatti's Ex-Wife, Lisa Storie-Avenatti: Who Is the Ex-Wife of Stormy Daniels' Attorney? |first=Dontei |last=Wynter |date=March 26, 2018 |accessdate=August 28, 2018 |url=https://www.earnthenecklace.com/michael-avenattis-ex-wife-lisa-avenatti/ |location=[[Concord, Ontario|Concord]], Ontario}}</ref>\n|children     = 3\n|education    = [[Saint Louis University]]<br/>[[University of Pennsylvania]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br/>[[George Washington University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|occupation   = Attorney\n|years_active = 1992\u20132020\n|website      = {{URL|avenatti.com|Official website}}\n}}\n\n'''Michael John Avenatti''' (born February 16, 1971) is an American attorney and convicted felon, best known for his representation of adult-film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] in [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|her lawsuits]] against President [[Donald Trump]], and his conviction for attempting to extort millions of dollars from sports apparel company [[Nike,_Inc.|Nike]].<ref name=\"CNBC\">{{cite web |last1=Mangan |first1=Dan |title=Disgraced lawyer Michael Avenatti found guilty in Nike extortion trial |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/02/14/disgraced-lawyer-michael-avenatti-found-guilty-in-nike-extortion-trial.html |website=CNBC | date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Michael Avenatti has been found guilty on all counts in Nike extortion trial |url=https://edition.cnn.com/2020/02/14/us/michael-avenatti-verdict/index.html |website=CNN| last=Cooper|first=Aaron|last2=Simon|first2=Darran|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Dienst |first1=Jonathan |title=Michael Avenatti Guilty on All Counts in Nike Extortion Trial |website=NBC New York |url=https://www.nbcnewyork.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/michael-avenatti-guilty-on-all-counts-in-nike-extortion-trial/2287069/ |date=14 February 2020|accessdate=14 February 2020}}</ref> His firm has represented various celebrity defendants and has filed suits against [[Fortune 100]] companies.<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.superlawyers.com/california-southern/article/the-scourge-of-kpmg/2afc085d-5bb4-472a-bc5c-4a9ca16915ef.html|title=Michael J. Avenatti \u2013 California Lawyers \u2013 The Scourge of KPMG|publisher=Superlawyers.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-kimberlyclark-lawsuit/kimberly-clark-faces-500-million-lawsuit-over-ebola-protection-gear-idUSKBN0IJ1VV20141030|title=Kimberly-Clark faces $500 million suit over Ebola protection gown|date=October 30, 2014|publisher=Reuters}}</ref> He has appeared on broadcast television as well as in print as a legal commentator and as a representative for prominent clients. He was also a race car driver, having participated in races in the United States and Europe.<ref name=\"driverdb.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.driverdb.com/drivers/michael-avenatti/|title=Michael Avenatti \u2013 Racing career profile|publisher=Driver Database}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti represented adult-film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] in [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal|her lawsuits]] against President [[Donald Trump]] in an attempt to void a [[non-disclosure agreement]] she had signed. Avenatti also represented Daniels in a related defamation suit against Trump.  Before [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court Justice]] [[Brett Kavanaugh]] was confirmed, Avenatti introduced a written declaration in September 2018 accusing Kavanaugh of spiking drinks at parties for the purpose of allowing girls to be gang raped when he was in high school.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/read-full-sworn-statement-from-brett-kavanaugh-accuser-julie-swetnick.html|title=Read the full sworn statement from Julie Swetnick, the third woman to accuse Supreme Court nominee Brett Kavanaugh of sexual misconduct|date=September 26, 2018|publisher=CNBC}}</ref> The accuser later repudiated the declaration in an interview with [[NBC News]], claiming Avenatti had misrepresented her allegations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/woman-kavanaugh-declaration-claims-avenatti-twisted-words-2018-10|title=A witness to alleged misconduct by Kavanaugh says Michael Avenatti 'twisted my words,' and that she only 'skimmed' her sworn declaration|date=October 26, 2018|publisher=Business Insider}}</ref>\n\nOn several occasions starting in March 2019, Avenatti was indicted in California and New York on multiple federal counts including tax evasion, extortion, fraud, and embezzlement. In June 2019, the [[State Bar of California]] filed a proceeding to \"involuntarily\" enroll Avenatti as an inactive attorney\u2014in effect, to suspend him from practicing law in California\u2014based on evidence that, according to the State Bar, could lead to Avenatti's [[disbarment]].<ref name = \"2019-06-05 CalBar Application\"/> Avenatti had denied all the charges. On February 14, 2020, Avenatti was convicted of all charges against him in the New York court. Avenatti is currently held in [[Metropolitan Correctional Center, New York|New York\u2019s Metropolitan Correctional Center]] while he awaits sentencing for his extortion conviction in the New York case. He faces potentially more than 40 years in prison.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/media/cnn-darling-michael-avenatti-nike|title=Ex-CNN darling Michael Avenatti convicted of trying to extort Nike|website=FOX News|language=en|access-date=2020-02-14}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|last=Stempel|first=Jonathan|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-avenatti-idUSKBN2082EB|title=Celebrity lawyer Michael Avenatti is found guilty in Nike extortion case|date=2020-02-14|work=[[Reuters]]|access-date=2020-02-14|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/Y1MwY|archive-date=2020-02-14|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn on February 16, 1971, in [[Sacramento, California|Sacramento]], California, Avenatti spent his early childhood in [[Colorado]] and [[Utah]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/lifestyle/style/michael-avenatti-the-adrenaline-fueled-lawyer-taking-on-donald-trump/2018/03/25/3ef5cbdc-2e88-11e8-b0b0-f706877db618_story.html|title=Michael Avenatti, the adrenaline-fueled lawyer taking on President Trump|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|last=Roig-Franzia|first=Manuel|date=March 25, 2018|access-date=April 17, 2018}}</ref> His father was a manager for [[Anheuser-Busch]].<ref name = Ball>{{cite news |last1=Ball |first1=Molly |last2=Abramson|first2=Alana|title=Michael Avenatti's Past Won't Stop Him From Running in 2020 |url=http://time.com/5434317/michael-avenatti/ |publisher=Time Magazine |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref> He moved with his family to [[Chesterfield, Missouri|Chesterfield]], Missouri, a suburb of [[St. Louis]], in 1982, where he attended [[Parkway Central High School]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stltoday.com/lifestyles/columns/joe-holleman/porn-star-stormy-daniels-lawyer-graduated-from-parkway-central/article_8ce4cfef-818e-58db-8250-a8f7d317effa.html|last=Holleman|first=Joe|title=Porn star Stormy Daniels' lawyer graduated from Parkway Central |work=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=March 8, 2018 |accessdate=March 24, 2018}}</ref> After graduating in 1989, Avenatti attended [[Saint Louis University]] for one year before transferring to the [[University of Pennsylvania]], where he graduated with a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in [[political science]] in 1996. While in college, he worked as an opposition researcher for [[Rahm Emanuel]]'s political consulting firm.<ref name = Ball/>\n\nAvenatti was wait-listed for [[George Washington University Law School]] (GW) and attended its night school program,<ref>https://abc3340.com/news/nation-world/avenatti</ref> during which he worked with Professor [[Jonathan Turley]] on constitutional issues relating to the [[Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act]] (FISA).<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/> In 2000, he graduated [[Order of the Coif]] and first in class with a [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]]<ref>[http://time.com/5434317/michael-avenatti/ \" by Molly Ball and Alana Abramson, ''TIME'',  October 25, 2018. Retrieved June 6, 2019.]</ref><ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/>  In 2003, his ''alma mater'' established the Michael J. Avenatti Award for Excellence in Pre-Trial and Trial Advocacy, after Avenatti made five figure donations to the school. The annual award is given to the member of the graduating Juris Doctor class who demonstrates excellence in [[pre-trial]] and trial advocacy. Avenatti was awarded GW's Alumni Recognition Award, in 2010.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www2.gwu.edu/~magazine/archive/2010_law_winter/dept_philanthropy.html|title=GW Magazine|publisher=George Washington University}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nWhile in college and later in law school, Avenatti worked at The Research Group, a political [[opposition research]] and media firm run by [[Rahm Emanuel]] (later [[White House Chief of Staff]] for President [[Barack Obama]], and [[Mayor of Chicago]]).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chicagomag.com/Chicago-Magazine/August-1992/Rahm-Emanuel-during-the-Bill-Clinton-Years/|title=A Rahm for the Money|last=Jannot|first=Mark|date=August 3, 1992|website=Chicago Magazine|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.chicagotribune.com/news/nationworld/politics/ct-stormy-daniels-lawyer-michael-avenatti-20180326-story.html|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer saw 'soft underbelly of politics' while working for Rahm Emanuel|last=Roig-Franzia|first=Manuel|date=March 26, 2018|work=Chicago Tribune|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> Avenatti worked on over 150 Democratic and Republican campaigns in 42 states while studying at George Washington University.<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\" />\n\nAfter law school, Avenatti worked at [[O'Melveny & Myers]] in Los Angeles, California, alongside [[Daniel M. Petrocelli]], who previously represented the [[Ron Goldman]] family in its case against [[O.J. Simpson]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcnews.com/id/5190480/ns/dateline_nbc-newsmakers/t/man-behind-simpson-guilty-verdict/#.WhI087Q-eqA|title=Man behind Simpson guilty verdict|date=June 14, 2004|publisher=NBC News}}</ref> He assisted Petrocelli on multiple legal matters, including the representation of singer [[Christina Aguilera]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/40609/christina-s-court-fight|title=Christina's Court Fight|last=Farache|first=Emily|date=October 18, 2000|website=E! Online|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref> and litigation surrounding the movie ''[[K-19: The Widowmaker]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.eonline.com/news/41182/harrison-ford-sub-drama-draws-fire|title=Harrison Ford Sub Drama Draws Fire|last=Grossberg|first=Josh|date=February 17, 2001|website=E! Online|access-date=June 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.vanityfair.com/news/2018/03/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-attorney-relishes-his-role-as-trump-nemesis|title=The President May Be Able to Fire Mueller, but He Can't Fire Me|last=Hagan|first=Joe|date=March 23, 2018|work=The Hive|access-date=June 12, 2018|publisher=Vanity Fair|language=en}}</ref> and worked extensively for [[Don Henley]] and [[Glenn Frey]] of the musical group [[the Eagles]], including in a suit brought by former bandmate [[Don Felder]] against the group and [[Irving Azoff]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2002/dec/08/business/fi-eagles-8|title=Reborn Eagles Lose Peaceful, Easy Feeling|first=Jeff|last=Leeds|date=December 8, 2002|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref><ref name=\"superlawyers.com\" />\n\nAvenatti later joined Greene Broillet & Wheeler, a Los Angeles [[boutique law firm]]. While there, he handled a number of high-profile cases, including a $10 million defamation case against [[Paris Hilton]] which was resolved amicably by the parties before going to trial,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://people.com/celebrity/paris-hilton-settles-10-million-defamation-suit/|title=Paris Hilton Settles $10 Million Defamation Suit|date=August 23, 2007|work=People}}</ref> settled an idea-theft lawsuit relating to the show ''[[The Apprentice (U.S. TV series)|The Apprentice]]'' and against producers [[Mark Burnett]] and [[Donald Trump]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/entertainment/gossip/confidential/stormy-daniels-lawyer-sued-trump-paris-hilton-article-1.3861088|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer has negotiated settlements with Donald Trump and Paris Hilton |last=Niemietz|first=Brian|date=March 7, 2018|work=New York Daily News|access-date=June 12, 2018|language=en-US}}</ref> and a $40 million embezzlement lawsuit involving [[KPMG]].<ref name=\"superlawyers.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB114359862516210767|title=KPMG Settles Targus Audit Case|first=David|last=Reilly|date=March 29, 2006|work=The Wall Street Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2007, Avenatti formed the law firm Eagan Avenatti, LLP (formerly known as Eagan O'Malley & Avenatti, LLP) with offices in [[Newport Beach, California|Newport Beach]], Los Angeles and [[San Francisco, California|San Francisco]], California. The firm launched many high-profile lawsuits including one over allegedly defective hospital gowns.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/60-minutes-investigates-medical-gear-sold-during-ebola-crisis/|title=60 Minutes investigates medical gear sold during Ebola crisis|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=May 1, 2016|website=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref>  He has since appeared on ''[[60 Minutes]]'' three times in connection with cases he has handled.<ref name=\"cbsnews.com\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/final-resting-place-cemeteries-lack-oversight/3/|title=Final resting place: Cemeteries lack oversight|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=May 21, 2012|website=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/stormy-daniels-describes-her-alleged-affair-with-donald-trump-60-minutes-interview/|title=Stormy Daniels describes her alleged affair with Donald Trump|last=Cooper|first=Anderson|date=March 28, 2018|work=CBS News|access-date=May 28, 2018|language=en}}</ref> Avenatti has also served as lead counsel on a number of historically large cases, including an April 2017 $454 million verdict after a jury trial in Federal Court in Los Angeles in a fraud case against [[Kimberly-Clark]] and [[Halyard Health]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/business/la-fi-hospital-gowns-20170410-story.html|title=Hospital gowns didn't protect as promised, jury says in $454-million fraud verdict|date=April 10, 2017|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref> later reduced to a $21.7 million verdict upon appeal,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.law.com/therecorder/2018/04/11/stormy-daniels-lawyer-avenatti-fights-to-save-huge-punitive-award-against-kimberly-clark/?slreturn=20180403234724|title=Stormy Daniels Lawyer Avenatti Fights to Save Huge Punitive Award Against Kimberly-Clark {{!}} The Recorder|last=Greene|first=Jenna|date=April 11, 2018|work=The Recorder|access-date=May 4, 2018}}</ref> an $80.5 million class-action settlement against [[Service Corporation International]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://jewishjournal.com/news/los_angeles/127210/|title=Eden Memorial Park settles lawsuit in $80.5 million deal|work=Jewish Journal|first=Jared|last=Sichel|date=February 27, 2014}}</ref> and a $41 million jury verdict against KPMG.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law.com/njlawjournal/almID/1202425263932/|title=KPMG Assessed $41 Million for Failing to Divulge Fraud Revealed in Audit|website=New Jersey Law Journal}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013, Avenatti formed a company, Global Baristas, to buy [[Seattle]]-based [[Tully's Coffee]] out of [[bankrupt]]cy.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/best-states/washington/articles/2018-03-09/report-tullys-coffee-closing-stores-due-to-lack-of-coffee|title=Report: Tully's Stores Run Out of Coffee as Rebranding Looms|website=Usnews.com|accessdate=April 16, 2018}}</ref> Avenatti first formed a partnership with actor [[Patrick Dempsey]], but Dempsey later backed away from the venture after a short legal battle that resulted in a settlement.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/dempsey-walks-away-from-tullyrsquos-after-suing-partner/|title=Dempsey walks away from Tully's after suing partner|date=August 23, 2013|work=Seattle Times}}</ref> Since 2015, Global Baristas has been named in more than 50 lawsuits in state and federal courts for breach of contract, unpaid bills, and unpaid taxes.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/before-stormy-daniels-her-attorney-faced-allegations-of-dubious-business-dealings/|title=Before Stormy Daniels, her attorney faced allegations of dubious business dealings at Tully's Coffee|last=Kamb|first=Lewis|date=April 7, 2018|work=Seattle Times|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, Avenatti prevailed against the [[National Football League]] (NFL) following a jury trial in [[Dallas]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dallasnews.com/news/news/2015/03/12/dallas-jury-awards-76000-to-super-bowl-seat-plaintiffs-finds-no-fraud-by-nfl|title=Dallas jury awards $76,000 to Super Bowl seat plaintiffs, finds no fraud by NFL|date=March 12, 2015|work=Dallas News|access-date=May 10, 2018|language=en}}</ref> He later pursued a class-action suit on behalf of fans who showed up for [[Super Bowl XLV]] with tickets that didn't correspond to actual seats but the courts in Texas declined to certify the class.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2016, Avenatti filed another class action lawsuit against the NFL, this time on behalf of ticket-holders to the annual [[Pro Football Hall of Fame Game|Hall of Fame Game]], which was cancelled a few hours before kickoff.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/09/hall-of-fame-non-game-lawsuit-appears-to-be-looming/|title=Hall of Fame Non-Game lawsuit appears to be looming|last=Florio|first=Mike|date=August 9, 2016|work=ProFootballTalk|access-date=May 10, 2018|publisher=NBC Sports|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2016/08/11/class-action-filed-in-ohio-over-hall-of-fame-non-game/|title=Class action filed in Ohio of Hall of Fame Non-Game|last=Florio|first=Mike|date=August 11, 2016|website=ProFootballTalk|publisher=NBC Sports|accessdate=May 10, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, a Florida man named Gerald Tobin alleged Avenatti failed to pay him $28,700 for private investigatory work. As a result, Avenatti's firm was abruptly forced into bankruptcy.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\">{{cite web|url=https://edition.cnn.com/2018/06/01/politics/avenatti-bankruptcy-lawsuit-stormy/index.html|title=Exclusive: How a 'nobody' ex-con pushed Avenatti law firm into bankruptcy}}</ref> In various news reports, including work done by CNN, Tobin was found to be an ex-con with four decades of convictions and jail time and not a licensed investigator. Tobin's claim forced Avenatti to cancel a deposition in an unrelated lawsuit days later, raising the question of collusion between Avenatti and Tobin. The issue was resolved when the pair entered into a [[non-disclosure agreement]], and Avenatti paid Tobin the $28,700.<ref name=\"edition.cnn.com\"/>\n\nIn 2018, Avenatti's law firm was subjected to a $10 million judgment in U.S. bankruptcy court.<ref name = \"Finnegan\"/> Avenatti has also defaulted on a $440,000 judgment in back taxes, penalties, and interest that he was personally obligated to pay under another bankruptcy settlement. The U.S. Attorney's office asserted in court that a motion seeking payment would soon be filed against Avenatti.<ref name=\"Finnegan\">{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-bankruptcy-20180522-story.html|title=Law firm of Stormy Daniels' attorney hit with $10-million judgment|last=Finnegan|first=Michael|date=May 22, 2018|work=[[Los Angeles Times]]|accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref> Eagan Avenatti had been in Chapter 11 bankruptcy proceedings and, in December 2017, had agreed to pay $4.8 million in unpaid fees to a former partner, $2 million in back taxes, and $1 million to other creditors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.law360.com/articles/1023444/judge-oks-eagan-avenatti-s-exit-from-ch-11|title=Judge OKs Eagan Avenatti's Exit From Ch. 11|last1=Bolado|first1=Carolina|publisher=Lexis Law 360|accessdate=March 19, 2018}}</ref> In June 2018, the former partner filed a motion in U.S. bankruptcy court asking for a lien on any and all legal fees Avenatti's firm might collect, up to $10 million, from clients in 54 cases including his representation of Stormy Daniels.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lawyer moves to seize Stormy Daniels' crowdfunding cash in Avenatti spat |url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-stormy-daniels-avenatti-20180613-story.html |accessdate=June 13, 2018 |publisher=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2018, a few days after [[Michael Avenatti#Personal life|his arrest]] on suspicion of domestic violence, Avenatti's law firm was evicted from its office in Newport Beach after skipping $213,000 worth of rent payments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/politics/avenattis-law-firm-evicted-from-california-offices-over-unpaid-213g-rent|title=Avenatti's law firm evicted from California offices over unpaid $213G rent|last1=Mikeleonis|first1=Lukas|publisher=Fox News|accessdate=November 17, 2018}}</ref> In January 2019, a former client filed arbitration against Avenatti, alleging misuse of settlement funds Eagan Avenatti LLP had received in trust.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/former-client-accuses-michael-avenatti-of-operating-law-firm-like-a-ponzi-scheme|title=Former Client Accuses Michael Avenatti of Operating Law Firm Like a 'Ponzi Scheme'|author=Betsy Briquelet and Kate Woodruff|date=January 23, 2019|access-date=January 29, 2019|language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2019 the California State Bar filed a 573 page petition to enroll Avenatti in involuntary inactive status pending the outcome of the criminal cases and the disciplinary action which will be filed against him. The primary basis for the action was Avenatti's alleged embezzlement of $1,600,000 in funds from client Greg Barela.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/06/04/politics/avenatti-california-bar/index.html|title=The California State Bar has taken the first step to disbar Michael Avenatti|last=Silverman|first=Hollie|date=June 4, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=4 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Racing===\nSince 2010, Avenatti has raced as a driver in approximately 33 sportscar races, including various [[American Le Mans Series]], [[FIA World Endurance Championship]], [[Porsche Supercup]] and [[United SportsCar Championship]] races in the United States and in Europe. These races have included the [[24 Hours of Daytona]], [[12 Hours of Sebring]], [[2012 Petit Le Mans]], and the [[Long Beach Grand Prix]].<ref name=\"driverdb.com\"/> Avenatti had been planning to race the [[2013 24 Hours of Le Mans]], but replaced himself with [[Patrick Long]] a few weeks before the event because scheduling conflicts had arisen with his other business interests.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://autoweek.com/article/alms/patrick-long-join-patrick-dempsey-and-dempseydel-piero-racing-le-mans |title=Patrick Long to Join Patrick Dempsey and Dempsey/Del Piero Racing for Le Mans |author=Staff |work=[[Autoweek]] |date=May 29, 2013 |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref> At the [[2015 24 Hours of Le Mans]], Avenatti teamed up with Saudi Prince [[Abdulaziz bin Turki Al Saud]] and Polish driver [[Jakub Giermaziak|Jakub \"Kuba\" Giermaziak]] in the No. 66 JMW Motorsport [[Ferrari 458]] Italia. The team placed seventh in its class.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fiawec.com/en/driver/265 |title=FIA Driver Categorisation \u2013 Michael Avenatti |publisher=[[FIA World Endurance Championship]] |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://sportscar365.com/lemans/lemans24/avenatti-le-mans-lived-up-to-the-expectation-level-and-then-some/ |title=Avenatti: 'Le Mans Lived Up to the Expectation Level and Then Some' |date=June 16, 2015 |author=John Dagys |work=Sportscar 365 |access-date=May 11, 2018}}</ref>\n\n; 24 Hours of Le Mans results\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Team\n! Co-drivers\n! Car\n! Class\n! Laps\n! {{Tooltip|Pos.|Overall position}}\n! {{Tooltip|Class<br>pos.|Class p8osition}}\n|-\n! [[2015 24 Hours of Le Mans|2015]]\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|GBR}} JMW Motorsport\n|align=\"left\"| {{flagicon|POL}} [[Kuba Giermaziak]]<br>{{flagicon|KSA}} [[Abdulaziz bin Turki Al Saud|Abdulaziz al Faisal]]\n|align=\"left\"| [[Ferrari 458 Italia GT2]]\n| GTE<br>Am\n| 320\n| 36th\n| 7th\n|-\n|}\n\n===Stormy Daniels lawsuits===\n{{Main|Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump scandal}}\n[[File:Stormy Daniels and Michael Avenatti in 2018.png|thumb|Stormy Daniels and Michael Avenatti in 2018]]\nIn March 2018, Avenatti filed a lawsuit on behalf of adult film actress [[Stormy Daniels]] seeking to invalidate [[Stormy Daniels\u2013Donald Trump legal dispute|a 2016 non-disclosure agreement]] regarding an alleged affair with Donald Trump in 2006, claiming that Daniels had been payed off by Trump's lawyer [[Michael Cohen (lawyer)|Michael Cohen]] not to disclose information covered by the NDA. The [[non-disclosure agreement]] had been negotiated in the final days of the [[2016 U.S. Presidential campaign]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/03/06/business/06reuters-usa-trump-daniels.html|title=Stormy Daniels Sues Trump Over 'Hush Agreement'|last=Hay|first=Andrew|date=March 6, 2018|access-date=June 12, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308042121/https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2018/03/06/business/06reuters-usa-trump-daniels.html|archive-date=March 8, 2018|url-status=dead|agency=Reuters|website=The New York Times}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/investigations/porn-star-stormy-daniels-sues-president-trump/2018/03/06/1ad8e60a-21a7-11e8-a589-763893265565_story.html|title=Porn actress Stormy Daniels sues Trump, says hush agreement is null because he didn't sign it|last1=Reinhard|first1=Beth|last2=Sellers|first2=Frances Stead|date=March 6, 2018|work=Washington Post|last3=Brown|first3=Emma}}{{subscription only}}</ref> Avenatti also represented Daniels in a related defamation suit against Trump. In October 2018, a federal judge dismissed the defamation lawsuit and ordered Daniels to pay Trump's legal fees. Avenatti said he would appeal that decision; Daniels later said that Avenatti had initiated the suit against her wishes.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/judge-throws-out-stormy-danielss-lawsuit-against-trump/2018/10/15/402935e8-d0cc-11e8-b2d2-f397227b43f0_story.html|title=Judge throws out Stormy Daniels's defamation lawsuit against Trump|website=Washington Post|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/11/28/us/stormy-daniels-michael-avenatti.html|title=Stormy Daniels Says Michael Avenatti Filed Trump Defamation Suit Against Her Wishes|last=Stevens|first=Matt|date=November 28, 2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 29, 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti was a frequent guest on talk shows and cable news programs to discuss the cases, logging 108 [[CNN]] and [[MSNBC]] appearances between March 7 and May 10, 2018.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/stormy-daniels-lawyer-michael-avenatti-ready-his-star-turn-n867771|title=Stormy Daniels' lawyer Michael Avenatti is ready for his star turn|last=Atkinson|first=Claire|date=April 20, 2018|work=[[NBCNews.com]]|accessdate=May 7, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Joe|first1=Concha|title=Michael Avenatti has appeared on CNN and MSNBC 108 times since March 7, says Free Beacon|url=http://thehill.com/homenews/media/387325-michael-avenatti-has-appeared-on-cnn-and-msnbc-108-times-since-march-7-says|accessdate=May 11, 2018|agency=The Hill}}</ref> He also gained a large following on [[Twitter]]; he ended his tweets about the case and other Trump-related matters with the Twitter [[hashtag]] \"#basta\"\u2013the Italian word for \"enough.\"<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-stormy-trump-20180407-story.html|title=Trump meets his match: Stormy Daniels' combative lawyer Michael Avenatti|author1=Michael Finnegan|author2=Maura Dolan|publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=April 7, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn May 2018, Avenatti released records showing multiple large payments, some from major corporations, into the bank account Cohen had used to pay Daniels.<ref>{{cite news|title=Michael Avenatti claims Michael Cohen received payments from firm controlled by Russian oligarch|url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-lawyer-claims-cohen-received-payments-from-russian-oligarchs-company/|accessdate=May 14, 2018|publisher=CBS News|date=May 9, 2018}}</ref> Cohen's lawyers subsequently argued that some of the transactions released by Avenatti involved a different Michael Cohen, but they did not dispute the larger deposits.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsweek.com/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-wrong-person-bank-records-novartis-att-919029|title=Stormy Daniels's Attorney Michael Avenatti Got the Wrong Michael Cohen in Bank Records|last=Edevane|first=Gillian|date=May 10, 2018|work=Newsweek|accessdate=May 24, 2018}}</ref> The US Treasury Department opened an investigation into how Avenatti gained information from Cohen's private bank records.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/politics/2018/05/09/michael-cohen-treasury-inspectors-investigate-leak-bank-records/596686002/|title=Treasury investigates possible leak of bank records for Trump lawyer Michael Cohen|last=Korte|first=Gregory|date=May 9, 2018|work=USA Today|access-date=May 28, 2018|last2=Schouten|first2=Fredreka|language=en}}</ref> Avenatti had also filed a motion to join the federal investigation of Michael Cohen. The federal judge issued Avenatti \"a choice\" that if he wanted to join he would have to end what the judge called his \"publicity tour\" of TV appearances and tweets about the case.<ref name=\"TIME\">{{cite news |title=Stormy Daniels' Attorney Drops Motion to Represent Her in Michael Cohen Probe |url=http://time.com/5295578/michael-avenatti-dropped-stormy-daniels-case-end-publicity-tour/ |accessdate=May 30, 2018 |publisher=TIME}}</ref> Avenatti withdrew the motion, and appeared on MSNBC that same day.<ref name=\"TIME\"/>\n\nIn early March 2019 Daniels terminated her arrangement with Avenatti, replacing him with attorney Clark Brewster. Later that month when federal charges against Avenatti were announced, she said \"Knowing what I know now about Michael, I\u2019m saddened but not shocked regarding his arrest.\"<ref name = Mangan/>\n\n===Immigration===\nAvenatti provided a video to [[MSNBC]] which aired on the June 25, 2018, episode of ''[[The Rachel Maddow Show]]'', a \"secretly shot\" video of a child in the custody of immigration officials who was separated from her mother. The video was leaked by a former employee whom Avenatti represents.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Samuels |first1=Brett |title=Former migrant detention facility worker leaks footage from inside facility to MSNBC |url=http://thehill.com/latino/394095-former-migrant-detention-facility-worker-leaks-footage-from-inside-facility-to-msnbc |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=June 26, 2018}}</ref> The leaked video was part of the response to the [[Trump administration family separation policy]].\n\n===Julie Swetnick allegations===\n{{Main|Brett Kavanaugh Supreme Court nomination}}\n[[File:2018 09 26 letter by US Senate Judiciary Committee Democrats on affidavit of Julie Swetnick.png|thumb|U.S. Senate Judiciary Committee Democrats on affidavit of Julie Swetnick]]\nIn September 2018, as the nomination of [[Brett Kavanaugh]] to the [[U.S. Supreme Court]] was being evaluated in the Senate, two women accused him of inappropriate sexual conduct while in high school or college. Avenatti then announced that he had a client who made additional allegations against Kavanaugh, as both a witness and a victim of his inappropriate behavior, and that she would soon come forward publicly.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/09/24/politics/michael-avenatti-brett-kavanaugh-cnntv/index.html|title=Avenatti promises new Kavanaugh accuser to come forward in next 48 hours|last=Tatum|first=Sophie|date=September 25, 2018|work=CNN|accessdate=September 26, 2018}}</ref> On September 25, the woman was publicly identified by Avenatti as Julie Swetnick, a resident of [[Washington, D.C.]] and a 1980 graduate of [[Gaithersburg High School]] in Maryland. Swetnick claimed in a sworn [[affidavit]], signed under penalty of perjury, that Kavanaugh, as a high school student in the early 1980s, drank excessively and engaged in physically aggressive behavior toward girls. She said he was present at parties where girls were drugged and gang raped and that he participated in those activities. Swetnick also claims that she was gang raped at a party where Kavanaugh was present, although he did not personally participate in the attack.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://twitter.com/MichaelAvenatti/status/1044960428730843136/photo/1?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw%7Ctwcamp%5Etweetembed%7Ctwterm%5E1044960428730843136&ref_url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/michael-avenatti-identifies-kavanaugh-accuser-as-julie-swetnick.html|title=Michael Avenatti on Twitter|work=Twitter|access-date=September 26, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref name = new>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/09/26/michael-avenatti-identifies-kavanaugh-accuser-as-julie-swetnick.html|title=New Kavanaugh accuser Julie Swetnick details parties where girls allegedly were drugged and raped|last=Breuninger|first=Dan Mangan, Kevin|date=September 26, 2018|work=CNBC|access-date=September 26, 2018}}</ref> Kavanaugh retorted, \"I don't know who this is and this never happened.\" September 26 the Democrats on the Judiciary Committee sent a letter to Chairman Grassley requesting \"[i]n light of shocking new allegations detailed by Julie Swetnick\" that the vote be immediately canceled and that Grassley should support either the reopening of the FBI investigation or the withdrawal of Kavanaugh's nomination.<ref name = new/> In an NBC interview, Swetnick provided the names of four friends who went to the parties with her \u2013 however, one is deceased and another did not know her.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kavanaugh accuser Julie Swetnick speaks out on sexual abuse allegations |url=https://www.msn.com/en-za/news/other/kavanaugh-accuser-julie-swetnick-speaks-out-on-sexual-abuse-allegations/ar-BBNPJks |date=September 26, 2018|agency=NBC News}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti announced that he had a sworn declaration by another woman backing up Swetnick's accusations. Subsequently, NBC news reported that the unnamed declarant told them on September 30 (before Michael Avenatti released her sworn statement on October 3 with her name blacked out) that she never thought it was Kavanaugh spiking the punch, and that she never witnessed him act inappropriately towards girls. In a text to NBC News on October 4, the unnamed accuser reiterated, \"It is incorrect that I saw Brett spike the punch. I didn't see anyone spike the punch...I was very clear with Avenatti from day one,\" adding that she would never allow anyone to be abusive towards males or females in her presence. She also expressed that she had only given her sworn declaration a cursory look. The response to NBC news by Avenatti was that she read, signed and repeatedly stood behind the sworn declaration. The unnamed declarant contacted NBC news October 5 and reiterated her denial of ever seeing Kavanaugh spike punch or act inappropriately toward women, and charged Avenatti with twisting her words.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Snow |first1=Kate |last2=Schecter |first2=Anna |title=New questions raised about Avenatti claims regarding Kavanaugh |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/politics/justice-department/new-questions-raised-about-avenatti-claims-regarding-kavanaugh-n924596 |accessdate=October 27, 2018 |publisher=National Broadcasting Company |date=October 25, 2018}}</ref>\n\nKavanaugh was confirmed to the Supreme Court by a margin of 50-48, mostly along party lines. Several Democratic Senators blamed Avenatti as the Swetnick accusation \"gave Republicans an opportunity to shift the narrative away from Ford's allegations and make a broader case that the growing accusations of sexual misconduct amounted to an orchestrated Democratic smear campaign\". Senator [[Susan Collins]], a Republican swing vote, called the Swetnick allegation \"outlandish...[without] any credible supporting evidence\", and ended up supporting Kavanaugh's nomination. Senator [[Gary Peters]] said that Avenatti's allegations \"turns it into a circus atmosphere and certainly that's not where we should be\", while another Senate aide said that \"Democrats and the country would have been better off if Mr. Avenatti spent his time on his Iowa vanity project rather than meddling in Supreme Court fights\". Avenatti fired back, criticizing anonymous Democrats as \"cowards\", arguing that this showed \"failed leadership\" in the Democratic Party.<ref>[https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/06/politics/democrats-avenatti-swetnick-accusation/index.html Manu Raju, \"Democrats say Avenatti undercut their case against Kavanaugh\"], CNN Politics, October 8, 2018.</ref>\n\nSenate Judiciary Chairman [[Chuck Grassley]] referred Avenatti and Swetnick to the [[United States Department of Justice|Department of Justice]] for a possible criminal investigation over allegations they made false statements to Congress about now-Supreme Court Justice Brett Kavanaugh. Avenatti called the referral \"completely baseless.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2018/10/25/politics/julie-swetnick-justice-department-judiciary-committee/index.html|title=Judiciary chairman refers Swetnick, Avenatti to Justice Department|last=de Vogue|first=Ariane|date=October 25, 2018|website=CNN|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://thehill.com/homenews/senate/413153-grassley-refers-swetnick-avenatti-to-justice-dept-for-investigation|title=Grassley refers Swetnick, Avenatti to Justice Dept. for investigation|last=Carney|first=Jordain|date=October 25, 2018|website=The Hill|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/grassley-refers-avenatti-and-swetnick-to-justice-for-a-criminal-probe/2018/10/25/75ef7a02-d879-11e8-9559-712cbf726d1c_story.html|title=Grassley refers Avenatti and Swetnick to Justice for a criminal probe|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|date=October 25, 2018|website=Washington Post|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n===Potential 2020 presidential campaign===\nAvenatti expressed interest in [[2020 United States presidential election|running for President of the United States in 2020]]; he started a [[political action committee]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/09/us/politics/michael-avenatti-president.html|title=Michael Avenatti, Stormy Daniels's Lawyer, Eyes Another Gig: President|access-date=August 27, 2018|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Jennifer Epstein |last2=John McCormick |title=Avenatti Says He's Serious About Running Against Trump in 2020 |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2018-08-28/stormy-daniels-lawyer-says-he-s-serious-about-a-2020-campaign |accessdate=April 11, 2019 |work=Bloomberg |date=28 August 2018 |quote=Last week alone, Michael Avenatti hobnobbed with Democratic National Committee leaders in Chicago, started a political action committee to raise money for Democratic congressional candidates, and met with David Axelrod, former President Barack Obama\u2019s strategist.}}</ref> and held his first fundraiser at the Democratic Wing Ding in August.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Maggie Astor |title=Michael Avenatti Urges Democrats to Reject Michelle Obama's Advice on Trump |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/08/10/us/politics/michael-avenatti-michelle-obama-trump.html |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |work=The New York Times |issue=August 10, 2019 |quote=his keynote speech Friday night at the Democratic Wing Ding, a party fund-raiser in northern Iowa}}</ref> In September 2018, Avenatti said he would run in 2020 only against Trump or Pence.<ref>{{Citation|last=CBC News: The National|title=Lawyer for Stormy Daniels considers running for president|date=September 10, 2018|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=_DpHHB6nAbw&t=9m53s|access-date=September 13, 2018}}</ref> On November 1, 2018, Avenatti released his first political ad, which urged Americans to vote on November 6, 2018;<ref name=\"POL-20181101\">{{cite news |last=Koreck |first=Natasha |title=Avenatti launches his first political ad - The attorney wouldn't say how much he's spending on the digital spot that will run on Facebook and Twitter. |url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/11/01/avenatti-political-ad-953758 |date=November 1, 2018 |work=[[Politico]] |accessdate=November 1, 2018 }}</ref> ''[[the Washington Post]]'' ranked him a top 15 contender.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Aaron Blake |title=The top 15 Democratic presidential candidates for 2020, ranked |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/09/top-democratic-presidential-candidates-ranked/ |accessdate=March 26, 2019 |work=The Washington Post |date=November 9, 2019 |quote=Democrats are starting to warm to his brash, in-your-face style}}</ref> On December 4, 2018, Avenatti announced that he would not be a candidate for president of the United States in 2020. In a Twitter post, he announced \"I do not make this decision lightly \u2014 I make it out of respect for my family.\"<ref name=\"notrun\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2018/12/04/michael-avenatti-announces-he-will-not-run-for-president-in-2020.html|title=Michael Avenatti announces he will not run for president in 2020|newspaper=CNBC|author=Dan Mangan|date=December 4, 2018|accessdate=December 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Arrests and charges==\n===Domestic violence complaint===\nIn November 2018, Avenatti was arrested on suspicion of domestic violence.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Dylan |title=Michael Avenatti has reportedly been arrested for domestic violence |url=https://www.vox.com/2018/11/14/18095836/michael-avenatti-domestic-violence-arrest-stormy-daniels-2020-president |date=November 14, 2018 |website=Vox.com |publisher=Vox}}</ref> The [[Los Angeles Police Department]] (LAPD) later confirmed Avenatti was arrested for felony domestic violence and his bail was set at $50,000.<ref>{{cite web |title=LA Police Department |url=https://twitter.com/LAPDHQ/status/1062876803587432448 |website=Official Twitter |accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Michael Avenatti arrested on suspicion of domestic violence: LAPD |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/michael-avenatti-arrested-on-suspicion-of-domestic-violence-lapd |accessdate=November 15, 2018 |agency=Fox News Corp.}}</ref> An LAPD spokesperson said that the unidentified victim, later described as his girlfriend,<ref name=\"Lee_11/21/2018\"/> had \"visible injuries\" and that the case would be referred to the [[Los Angeles County District Attorney]] for prosecution.<ref name = \"Croucher\"/> Minutes after the reports of Avenatti's arrest, the Twitter account of Surefire Intelligence, a company created by the [[far-right]] [[conspiracy theorist]] [[Jacob Wohl]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/15/michael-avenatti-arrested-suspicion-domestic-violence/|title=Michael Avenatti arrested on suspicion of domestic violence, calls allegations 'completely bogus'|last=Viebeck|first=Elise|date=November 15, 2018|work=[[The Washington Post]]|access-date=February 10, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181217083813/https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2018/11/15/michael-avenatti-arrested-suspicion-domestic-violence/|archive-date=December 17, 2018|url-status=live|last2=Rosenberg|first2=Eli|last3=Paul|first3=Deanna|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref name=\"snopes_2018-11-16\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.snopes.com/news/2018/11/16/michael-avenatti-was-arrested-on-domestic-violence-charges-and-then-things-got-weird/|title=Michael Avenatti Was Arrested on Domestic Violence Charges, And Then Things Got Weird|last=Palma|first=Bethania|date=November 16, 2018|website=[[Snopes]]|language=en-US|access-date=February 11, 2019}}</ref> seemingly claimed responsibility for the arrest, tweeting a news story about it and adding \"Surefire Intelligence strikes again.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/if-surefire-intelligence-really-was-behind-false-avenatti-police-report-jacob-wohl-could-be-in-deep-trouble/|title=If Surefire Intelligence Really Was Behind False Avenatti Police Report, Jacob Wohl Could Be in Deep Trouble|last=Naham|first=Matt|date=November 15, 2018|website=[[Dan Abrams#Law & Crime|Law & Crime]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181116010027/https://lawandcrime.com/high-profile/if-surefire-intelligence-really-was-behind-false-avenatti-police-report-jacob-wohl-could-be-in-deep-trouble/|archive-date=November 16, 2018|url-status=live|accessdate=November 15, 2018|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\nAvenatti called the allegations \"completely bogus\" and \"fabricated and meant to do harm to my reputation.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mediaite.com/online/michael-avenatti-denies-alleged-domestic-violence-ive-never-been-physically-abusive-in-my-life/|title=Avenatti Denies 'Fabricated' Allegations of Domestic Violence: I've Never Been 'Physically Abusive in My Life'|website=www.mediaite.com|accessdate=November 15, 2018}}</ref> Both of his ex-wives issued statements that Avenatti had never been violent toward either of them.<ref name = \"Croucher\"/> The county district attorney declined to press charges, and referred the case to the city attorney for possible misdemeanor charges.<ref name=\"Lee_11/21/2018\">{{cite web | last=Lee | first=Michelle Ye Hee | title=Los Angeles prosecutors decline to file felony domestic abuse charges against Michael Avenatti | website=[[The Washington Post]] | date=November 21, 2018 | url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/los-angeles-prosecutors-decline-to-file-felony-domestic-abuse-charges-against-michael-avenatti/2018/11/21/c8ac3024-edd6-11e8-96d4-0d23f2aaad09_story.html | access-date=November 22, 2018}}</ref> On February 1, 2019, the city attorney's office announced that their investigation was complete, and that Avenatti would not be charged.<ref>{{cite news |last=Stack |first=Liam |date=February 1, 2019 |title=Michael Avenatti Will Not Be Charged With Domestic Violence, Officials Say |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/02/01/us/michael-avenatti-domestic-violence.html |work=The New York Times |location=New York, NY}}</ref>\n\n===Extortion charge===\nOn March 25, 2019, Avenatti was arrested in New York City, and federal prosecutors in the [[United States District Court for the Southern District of New York|Southern District of New York]] announced that they were charging Avenatti with attempting to [[Extortion|extort]] up to $25 million from U.S. athletic apparel and shoe company [[Nike, Inc.|Nike]] by threatening to make damaging charges against the company.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/michael-avenatti-charged-nike-extortion-2019-3|title=Michael Avenatti charged for attempting to extort more than $20 million from Nike|last=Sheth|first=Sonam|website=Business Insider|access-date=March 25, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/michael-avenatti-accused-of-trying-to-extort-nike-for-up-to-25m-feds-say|title=Michael Avenatti accused of trying to extort Nike for up to $25M, feds say|last=Sang|first=Lucia Suarez|last2=Chamberlain|first2=Samuel|date=March 25, 2019|website=[[Fox News]]|language=en-US|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti allegedly claimed that Nike improperly made payments to families of high school basketball players.<ref>{{cite news |date=March 25, 2019 |title=5 of the Most Explosive Details From the Michael Avenatti-Nike Extortion Case |author=Sheena Butler-Young |publisher=Fairchild Publications |work=Footwear News |url=https://footwearnews.com/2019/business/legal-news/michael-avenatti-nike-extortion-scandal-details-allegations-1202764390/ |accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> The arrest came about 15 minutes after Avenatti announced that he would be holding a press conference the next day, at which he claimed he would reveal information about a high school and college basketball scandal involving Nike.<ref name=\"Mangan\" /> \n\nDuring the afternoon of March 25, Avenatti and an unnamed co-conspirator were scheduled to meet with lawyers from Nike, at which prosecutors allege he would have offered to cancel the press conference in exchange for payment.<ref name = Mangan>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnbc.com/2019/03/25/michael-avenatti-to-be-charged-with-wire-and-bank-fraud.html|title=Stormy Daniels' ex-lawyer Michael Avenatti arrested for alleged $20 million extortion scheme against Nike, embezzling client's money, defrauding bank|last1=Mangan|first1=Dan|last2=Breuninger|first2=Kevin|date=March 25, 2019|work=CNBC|accessdate=March 25, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti's suspected co-conspirator was identified as [[Mark Geragos]].<ref name=\":2\" /> Avenatti was released on a $300,000 bond that evening.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/politics/live-news/michael-avenatti-charged/index.html|title=Lawyer Michael Avenatti charged: Live updates|date=March 25, 2019 |website=www.cnn.com|language=en|access-date=March 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn February 14, 2020, Avenatti was found guilty on all three counts related to the attempted extortion of Nike. He faces potentially more than 40 years in prison.<ref name=\"CNBC\" /><ref name=\":3\" />\n\n===Fraud and embezzlement charges===\nAlso on March 25, 2019, the [[U.S. Attorney for the Central District of California]], [[Nicola T. Hanna]], announced in Los Angeles the filing of a 197-page complaint accusing Avenatti of [[wire fraud]] and [[bank fraud]].<ref name = Mangan/> The indictment said that Avenatti had [[embezzlement|embezzled]] money from a client and had defrauded a Mississippi bank by submitting false tax returns to obtain more than $4 million in loans. Prosecutors also alleged that Avenatti had not filed personal tax returns for the years in question.<ref>{{cite news|title=Lawyer Michael Avenatti arrested, faces wire fraud and bank fraud charges|date=March 25, 2019|work=Los Angeles Times}}</ref>\n\nOn April 10, 2019, Avenatti was charged by a federal grand jury in [[Santa Ana, California]] of embezzling funds that his client, NBA player [[Hassan Whiteside]], had wired to him in January 2017 for the purpose of paying a settlement to his ex-girlfriend. Avenatti stands accused of withholding client funds and applying most of the settlement money of $1.75 million, along with his included $1 million fee, in order to invest $2.5 million in a share of a private jet. He is further accused of misrepresenting Whiteside\u2019s settlement payment as monthly installments, which he paid out until June 2018, totaling $194,000.  Federal agents subsequently seized a Honda HA-420 twin-engine jet from Santa Barbara Airport that was co-owned by Avenatti and former client, Indigo Systems co-founder William J. Parrish, as the latter was about to embark on a flight. Parrish successfully sued Avenatti in 2017 for $2.1 million for failure to repay a 2013 loan. Avenatti had not appeared in court to defend himself and is appealing that judgment. Avenatti denies the charges.<ref>{{cite web |title=Avenatti accused of embezzling nearly $2 million that NBA player paid ex-girlfriend |url=https://www.latimes.com/politics/la-na-pol-avenatti-hassan-whiteside-embezzlement-20190421-story.html |publisher=LA Times}}</ref><ref>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/04/22/michael-avenattis-alleged-embezzlement-included-millions-heats-hassan-whiteside/ \"Michael Avenatti\u2019s alleged embezzlement included payment from Heat\u2019s Hassan Whiteside\", by Des Bieler, April 22, 2019. Retrieved April 22, 2019.]</ref>\n\nOn April 11, 2019, 36 additional financial crime charges were announced by the U.S. Attorney for the Central District of California.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/04/11/politics/michael-avenatti-indicted-los-angeles/index.html|title=Michael Avenatti indicted on 36 counts|last=Orden|first=Erica|website=CNN|access-date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>[https://www.reuters.com/article/us-usa-crime-avenatti/lawyer-avenatti-charged-in-california-with-u-s-fraud-tax-crimes-idUSKCN1RN23B \"Avenatti, lawyer known as Trump foe, indicted for financial crimes\", by Jonathan Allen, ''Reuters'', April 11, 2019. Retrieved April 11, 2019.]</ref> Avenatti is accused of stealing money from clients to purchase a $5 million private jet he co-owned, as well as fraud related to tax documents and banking information.<ref name=Bever11April>{{cite news|work=The Washington Post|date=April 11, 2019|accessdate=April 11, 2019|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/politics/2019/04/11/michael-avenatti-hit-with-federal-charges-including-tax-fraud-embezzlement-report-says/ |title=Michael Avenatti charged with stealing millions from clients, using 'ill-gotten gains' for a private jet |first1=Lindsey|last1=Bever|first2=Devlin|last2=Barrett |first3=Mark |last3=Berman }}</ref> According to U.S. Attorney Hanna, \"[m]oney generated from one set of crimes was used to further other crimes, typically in the form of payments designed to string along victims.\" The purpose of his crimes was \"to prevent Mr. Avenatti\u2019s financial house of cards from collapsing.\"<ref name=Bever11April/> Vowing to \"fully fight\" the additional charges and appealing to the public to presume his innocence, Avenatti stated on Twitter that \"[f]or 20 years, I have represented Davids vs. Goliaths and relied on due process and our system of justice. Along the way, I have made many powerful enemies.\"<ref name=Bever11April/>\n\nOn May 22, 2019, Avenatti was charged with wire fraud and aggravated identity theft as a result of allegations that he stole money from former client [[Stormy Daniels]] while helping negotiate her 2018 book deal.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.cnn.com/2019/05/22/politics/michael-avenatti-stormy-daniels-indictment/index.html|title=Michael Avenatti charged with stealing $300,000 from former client Stormy Daniels|last=Orden|first=Erica|date=May 22, 2019|work=CNN|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"FraudChargesPBS\">{{cite web |title=Avenatti pleads not guilty to defrauding Stormy Daniels |url=https://www.pbs.org/newshour/politics/avenatti-pleads-not-guilty-to-defrauding-stormy-daniels |publisher=PBS |accessdate=May 28, 2019 |date=May 28, 2019}}</ref> Avenatti pleaded not guilty. Avenatti was released on a $300,000 bail bond on conditions that he notify authorities of any travel plans and that he have no contact with Daniels.<ref>[https://www.aol.com/article/news/2019/05/28/trump-foe-avenatti-pleads-not-guilty-to-ripping-off-stormy-daniels/23735913/ Brendan Pierson, \"Trump foe Avenatti pleads not guilty to ripping off Stormy Daniels\"], Reuters, 28 May 2019.</ref><ref name=\"FraudChargesPBS\"/>\n\n=== Disbarment proceeding in California ===\n\nOn June 5, 2019, the [[State Bar of California]] filed with the California State Bar Court a 573-page application, under [[California Codes|California Business and Professions Code]] section 6007(c)(2), to involuntarily enroll Avenatti as an inactive member of the bar.<ref name = \"2019-06-05 CalBar Application\">''Matter of Michael John Avenatti'', Case Number SBC-19-TE-30258,\n{{cite report\n|url=http://members.calbar.ca.gov/courtDocs/19-TE-30259-2.pdf\n|title=Corrected Application for Involuntary Inactive Enrollment\n|docket = |date = June 5, 2019\n|publisher = [[State Bar of California]]}}</ref> The State Bar Court is the court that decides whether a California attorney committed professional misconduct worthy of discipline, up to and including disbarment. The State Bar contends that the evidence submitted with the petition establishes that Avenatti has committed professional misconduct that has caused or is causing substantial harm to Avenatti's clients or to the public and that there is a substantial probability that Avenatti's professional misconduct will result in his [[disbarment]]. If the State Bar Court finds sufficient evidence to place Avenatti on involuntary inactive enrollment, the State Bar must initiate disciplinary proceedings within 45 days of the effective date of the order. If the State Bar Court rules on disbarment, the California Supreme Court must review and approve it.<ref>{{cite web |title=Rules of Procedure of the State Bar of California |url=https://www.calbar.ca.gov/Portals/0/documents/rules/Rules_Title5_Procedure.pdf |website=State Bar of California |accessdate=11 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n===January 2020 arrest===\nAvenatti was again arrested on January 14, 2020 during a recess in court for his disbarment proceedings, for violating the terms of a previous release, and was expected to appear in federal court in [[Santa Ana, California]] on January 15.<ref name=\"db\">{{cite news|url=https://www.thedailybeast.com/michael-avenatti-arrested-by-feds-at-california-state-bar-hearing|title=Michael Avenatti Arrested by Feds at California State Bar Hearing|work=The Daily Beast|date=January 15, 2020|accessdate=January 15, 2020|last=McGahan|first=Jason}}</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The Wall Street Journal]]'', Avenatti was scheduled to face trial in New York on charges of attempting to extort millions from Nike when a federal judge in California ordered him jailed until his trial in California. Prosecutors in California accused Avenatti of violating the conditions of his release by committing a series of financial crimes while free on bond: [[structuring]] currency transactions to avoid reporting requirements and concealing his personal assets from his creditors. U.S. Marshals were prepared to take Avenatti to Manhattan as early as January 17, 2020 for his trial on the New York charges. Avenatti's trial on the California charges was scheduled for the following May. Michael Avenatti also faced additional New York charges of wire fraud, identity theft, and embezzling almost $300,000 from [[Stormy Daniels]], his former client.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/michael-avenatti-faces-new-federal-charges-in-california-11579113731|title=Michael Avenatti Ordered Jailed Until Trial|last=Ramey|first=Corinne|last2=O'Brien|first2=Rebecca Davis|work=The Wall Street Journal|date=January 16, 2020|accessdate=January 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:2015 Honda HA-420 HondaJet 42000029 by D Ramey Logan.jpg|thumb|2015 Honda HA-420 HondaJet N227WP co-owned by Avenatti]]\n\nAvenatti was married for 13 years to Christine Carlin Avenatti, with whom he has two teenage daughters.<ref name=\"Croucher\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newsweek.com/michael-avenatti-denies-domestic-abuse-allegation-i-did-not-strike-my-ex-wife-1216461|title=Michael Avenatti Denies Domestic Abuse Allegation|last=Croucher|first=Shane|date=November 15, 2018|work=Newsweek|accessdate=November 16, 2018}}</ref> He married Lisa Storie in 2011. They have one son. Lisa Storie-Avenatti filed for divorce in December 2017.<ref name = Lisa/> In December 2018, according to court documents, Avenatti and his wife settled their divorce, with Avenatti agreeing to pay Lisa $1,947,540 in child and spousal support, and to transfer ownership of several assets to her, including five luxury wristwatches, a [[Frank Gehry]] sculpture, other artwork, and a leased 2017 [[Ferrari 488]] GT Spider, while his law firm would transfer to Lisa its interest in a 2015 Honda private jet.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Bill Bostock |title=Michael Avenatti reportedly will turn over cars, watches, and a jet to pay nearly $2 million to his estranged wife as part of their divorce agreement |url=https://www.businessinsider.com/avenatti-loses-thousands-in-lisa-storie-divorce-ferrari-watches-report-2018-12 |work=Business Insider |accessdate=May 23, 2019 |date=6 December 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe jet was later confiscated by federal agents at Santa Barbara Airport on April 10, 2019, during an asset seizure based on the tax, wire, and bankruptcy fraud indictment filed in the U.S. Central District Court of California.<ref>{{cite news |author1=William La Jeunesse |author2=Paulina Dedaj |title=Feds seize $4.5 million Avenatti plane amid tax scandal |url=https://www.foxnews.com/us/feds-seize-4-5-million-avenatti-plane-amid-tax-scandal |accessdate=May 23, 2019 |work=Fox News |date=April 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* {{section link|Michael Cohen (lawyer)#Essential Consultants LLC}}\n* {{section link|Michael Cohen (lawyer)#Payment to Stormy Daniels}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{sister project links|b=no|commons=Category:Michael Avenatti|d=Q43380465|n=no|q=Michael Avenatti|s=no|v=no|wikt=no|w=Michael Avenatti}}\n* {{Official}}\n* [https://www.dropbox.com/s/kiwkzgyzgztmrq1/WhatIBelieve.pdf Michael Avenatti \u2013 List of Political Beliefs (August 27, 2018)]\n* {{Racing-Reference driver|Michael_Avenatti}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Avenatti, Michael}}\n[[Category:1971 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American racing drivers]]\n[[Category:12 Hours of Sebring drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Daytona drivers]]\n[[Category:24 Hours of Le Mans drivers]]\n[[Category:American commentators]]\n[[Category:American extortionists]]\n[[Category:American Le Mans Series drivers]]\n[[Category:California Democrats]]\n[[Category:California lawyers]]\n[[Category:Donald Trump litigation]]\n[[Category:George Washington University Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People associated with O'Melveny & Myers]]\n[[Category:Racing drivers from California]]\n[[Category:Rolex Sports Car Series drivers]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Sacramento, California]]\n[[Category:WeatherTech SportsCar Championship drivers]]\n[[Category:University of Pennsylvania alumni]]\n", "name_user": "73.19.3.175", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Michael_Avenatti"}
{"title_page": "Joseph Cotten", "text_new": "{{short description|American film, stage and television actor}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=October 2012}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name           = Joseph Cotten\n| image          = Joseph-Cotten-1942.jpg\n| imagesize      =\n| caption        = Joseph Cotten in 1942\n| birth_name     = Joseph Cheshire Cotten Jr.\n| birth_date     = {{birth date|1905|05|15}}\n| birth_place    = [[Petersburg, Virginia]], U.S.\n| death_date     = {{death date and age|1994|02|06|1905|05|15}}\n| death_place    = [[Los Angeles]], California, U.S.<ref name=\"LA Times\"/>\n| burial_place = [[Blandford Cemetery]], Petersburg, Virginia\n| spouse         = {{Plainlist|\n*{{marriage|Lenore Kipp|1931|1960|end=died}}\n*{{marriage|[[Patricia Medina]]|1960|1994|end=his death}}\n}}\n| occupation     = Actor\n| height     ={{convert|6|ft|2|in|cm|sigfig=3|abbr=on}}\n| years_active   = 1930\u20131981\n| awards         = [[Venice Film Festival|Volpi Cup for Best Actor]]:<br>1949 ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]''\n}}\n\n'''Joseph Cheshire Cotten Jr.''' (May 15, 1905 \u2013 February 6, 1994) was an American film, stage, radio and television actor. Cotten achieved prominence on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]], starring in the original stage productions of ''[[The Philadelphia Story (play)|The Philadelphia Story]]'' and ''[[Sabrina Fair]]''.\n\nHe first gained worldwide fame in three [[Orson Welles]] films: ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' (1941), ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942), and ''[[Journey into Fear (1943 film)|Journey into Fear]]'' (1943), for which Cotten was also credited with the screenplay. He went on to become one of the leading Hollywood actors of the 1940s, appearing in films such as ''[[Shadow of a Doubt]]'' (1943), ''[[Love Letters (1945 film)|Love Letters]]'' (1945), ''[[Duel in the Sun (film)|Duel in the Sun]]'' (1946), ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]'' (1948), ''[[The Third Man]]'' (1949) and ''[[Niagara (film)|Niagara]]'' (1953). One of his final films was [[Michael Cimino]]'s ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'' (1980).\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Jo-Cotten-American-FC-1931.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Joseph Cotten modeled for ''[[The American Magazine]]'' (September 1931)]]\n{{multiple image\n<!-- Essential parameters -->\n| align     = right\n| direction = vertical\n| width     = 220\n<!-- Image 1 -->\n| image1    = WPA Federal Theater Project in New York-\"Horse Eats Hat\"-Joseph Cotton - NARA - 195723.tif\n| alt1      =\n| caption1  = Cotten in ''[[Horse Eats Hat]]'' (1936)\n<!-- Image 2 -->\n| image2    = Too-Much-Johnson-Cotten-Barrier.jpg\n| alt2      =\n| caption2  = Cotten and [[Edgar Barrier]] during the shooting of film sequences for the stage production ''[[Too Much Johnson]]'' (1938)\n<!-- Image 3 -->\n| image3    = Philadelphia-Story-Stage-5.jpg\n| alt3      =\n| caption3  = Cotten and [[Katharine Hepburn]] on Broadway in ''[[The Philadelphia Story (play)|The Philadelphia Story]]'' (1939)\n<!-- Image 4 -->\n| image4    = Citizen Kane-Jo Cotten.jpg\n| alt4      =\n| caption4  = Cotten is introduced in the [[Citizen Kane trailer|trailer]] for ''[[Citizen Kane]]'' (1941)\n<!-- Image 5 -->\n| image5    = The-Magnificent-Ambersons-2.jpg\n| alt5     =\n| caption5  = [[Dolores Costello]], [[Agnes Moorehead]], [[Anne Baxter]], Cotten, [[Tim Holt]] and [[Ray Collins (actor)|Ray Collins]] in ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942)\n<!-- Image 6 -->\n| image6    = Dolores del Rio-Joseph Cotten-Journey into Fear.jpg\n| alt6     =\n| caption6  = Cotten and [[Dolores del R\u00edo]] in ''[[Journey into Fear (1943 film)|Journey into Fear]]'' (1943)\n<!-- Image 7 -->\n| image7    = Mercury-Wonder-Show-Welles-Cotten.jpg\n| alt7      =\n| caption7  = George (Shorty) Chirello, Cotten, assistant Eleanor Counts and [[Orson Welles]] in ''[[The Mercury Wonder Show]]'' (1943)\n<!-- Image 8 -->\n| image8    = Welles-Hayworth-Cotten-1943.jpg\n| alt8      =\n| caption8  = Wedding of Orson Welles and [[Rita Hayworth]], with best man Cotten (September 7, 1943)\n<!-- Image 9 -->\n| image9    = Joseph Cotten in Shadow of a Doubt trailer.jpg\n| alt9     =\n| caption9  = Cotten in ''[[Shadow of a Doubt]]'' (1943)\n<!-- Image 10 -->\n| image10    = Jo-Cotten-FDR-LIFE-1944.jpg\n| alt10     =\n| caption10  = Members of the Independent Voters Committee of the Arts and Sciences for Roosevelt visit FDR at the White House (October 1944). From left: [[Van Wyck Brooks]], [[Hannah Weinstein|Hannah Dorner]], [[Jo Davidson]], [[Jan Kiepura]], Cotten, [[Dorothy Gish]], Dr. [[Harlow Shapley]]\n}}\nJoseph Cotten was born in 1905 in [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]], [[Virginia]], the first of three boys born for Joseph Cheshire Cotten, Sr., an assistant postmaster, and Sally Willson Cotten.<ref name=\"Vanity\">{{cite book |last=Cotten |first=Joseph |date=1987 |title= Vanity Will Get You Somewhere |location=San Francisco |publisher=[[Mercury House (publishers)|Mercury House]] |isbn=0-916515-17-6  }}</ref>{{Rp|224}} He grew up in the [[Tidewater region]] and showed an aptitude for drama and a gift for storytelling.\n\nIn 1923, when Cotten was 18, his family arranged for him to receive private lessons at the Hickman School of Expression in Washington, D.C., and underwrote his expenses.<ref name=\"los\">Joseph Cotten, 88, Dies Starred in `Citizen Kane,' `The Third Man': [ALL EDITIONS]\nLos Angeles Times 7 Feb 1994.</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCotten earned spending money playing professional football on Sundays, for $25 a quarter. After graduation, he earned enough money as a lifeguard at Wilcox Lake to pay back his family's loan, with interest.<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|4\u20137}}\n\nHe moved to Miami in 1925 and worked as an advertising salesman for ''The Miami Herald'' at $35 a week. He started performing at the Miami Civic Theatre, and worked there for five years, also reviewing the shows for the ''Herald''.<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n===Broadway===\nCotten moved to New York and went to work for [[David Belasco]] as an assistant stage manager. He understudied [[Melvyn Douglas]] in ''[[Tonight or Never (play)|Tonight or Never]]'' then took over Douglas' role for the Copley Theatre in Boston, where he worked on over 30 plays.<ref>Joseph Cotten, Film and Stage Actor, Dies; Starred in `Citizen Kane,' The Third Man': [FINAL Edition]\nWeil, Martin. The Washington Post 7 Feb 1994: d07.</ref>\n\nCotten struggled to find work in the depression so turned to modeling and acting in industrial films. He also performed on radio. Cotten made his Broadway debut in 1932 in ''Absent Friends'' which ran for 88 performances.<ref>[https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/absent-father-11648 ''Absent Father''] IBDB </ref>\n\nHe followed it with ''[[Jezebel (play)|Jezebel]]'' (1933), staged by [[Katherine Cornell]] and [[Guthrie McClintic]], which only had a short run.<ref>https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/jezebel-11805</ref>\n\nHe was in ''Loose Moments'' which ran for 8 performances.<ref>https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/loose-moments-11200</ref>\n\n===Orson Welles===\nIn 1934, Cotten met and became friends with [[Orson Welles]], a fellow cast member on [[CBS Radio]]'s ''[[The American School of the Air]]''.<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|30\u201331|date=January 2014}}  Welles regarded Cotten as a brilliant comic actor,<ref name=\"Lunches\">{{cite book |last1=Biskind |first1=Peter |authorlink1=Peter Biskind |last2=Jaglom |first2=Henry |authorlink2=Henry Jaglom |last3=Welles |first3= Orson |title=My Lunches with Orson: Conversations between Henry Jaglom and Orson Welles |publisher=[[Henry Holt and Company|Metropolitan Books]] |location=New York |date=2013 |isbn=978-0-8050-9725-2}}</ref>{{Rp|166}} and gave him the starring role in his [[Federal Theatre Project]] farce, '' [[Horse Eats Hat]]''<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|34}}<ref>{{cite book|last=Leaming|first=Barbara|title=Orson Welles|year=1985|publisher=Viking Penguin Inc|location=New York City|isbn=0-670-52895-1|page=[https://archive.org/details/orsonwellesbiogr00leam/page/114 114]|url=https://archive.org/details/orsonwellesbiogr00leam/page/114}}</ref> (September 26 \u2013 December 5, 1936).<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|334}} Cotten was sure that ''Horse Eats Hat'' won him the notice of his future Broadway co-star, [[Katharine Hepburn]].<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|34}}\n\nCotten said Welles later told him \"You're very lucky to be tall and thin and have curly hair. You can also move about the stage without running into the furniture. But these are fringe assets, and I'm afraid you'll never make it as an actor. But as a star, I think you well might hit the jackpot.\" <ref>Obituary: Joseph Cotten\nRule, Vera. The Guardian 8 Feb 1994.</ref>\n\nIn 1937, Cotten became an inaugural member of Welles's [[Mercury Theatre]] company, starring in its Broadway productions ''[[Caesar (Mercury Theatre)|Caesar]]'' as Publius; it ran for 157 performances.\n\nHe followed it with ''[[The Shoemaker's Holiday]]'' (1938) and ''[[Danton's Death]]'' (1938) for Welles. Cotten also performed in radio dramas presented on ''[[The Mercury Theatre on the Air]]'' and ''[[The Campbell Playhouse (radio series)|The Campbell Playhouse]]''.\n\nCotten made his film debut in the Welles-directed short, ''[[Too Much Johnson]]'', a comedy that was intended to complement the aborted 1938 Mercury stage production of [[William Gillette]]'s 1890 play. The film was never screened in public and was lost until 2013.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kehr |first=Dave |authorlink=Dave Kehr |date=August 7, 2013 |title=Early Film by Orson Welles Is Rediscovered |url= https://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/11/movies/early-film-by-orson-welles-is-rediscovered.html |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |access-date= 2016-07-12 }}</ref>\n\n===''The Philadelphia Story''===\nCotten returned to Broadway in 1939, creating the role of C. K. Dexter Haven opposite [[Katharine Hepburn]]'s Tracy Lord in the original production of [[Philip Barry]]'s ''[[The Philadelphia Story (play)|The Philadelphia Story]]''. The play ran for 417 performances at the [[Shubert Theatre (New York City)|Shubert Theatre]], and in the months before its extensive national tour a [[The Philadelphia Story (film)|film version]] was to be made by MGM. Cotten went to Hollywood, but discovered there that his stage success in ''The Philadelphia Story'' translated to, in the words of his agent [[Leland Hayward]], \"spending a solid year creating the [[Cary Grant]] role.\" Hayward suggested that they call Cotten's good pal, Orson Welles. \"He's been making big waves out here,\" Hayward said. \"Maybe nobody in Hollywood ever heard of the Shubert Theatre in New York, but everybody certainly knows about the Mercury Theatre in New York.\"<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|34\u201337|date=January 2014}}\n\n===''Citizen Kane''===\nAfter the success of Welles's ''[[The War of the Worlds (radio drama)|War of the Worlds]]'' 1938 [[Halloween]] radio broadcast, Welles gained a unique contract with [[RKO Pictures]]. The two-picture deal promised full creative control for the young director below an agreed budget limit, and Welles's intention was to feature the [[Mercury Theatre|Mercury Players]] in his productions. Shooting had still not begun on a Welles film after a year, but after a meeting with writer [[Herman J. Mankiewicz]] Welles had a suitable project.\n\nIn mid-1940, filming began on ''[[Citizen Kane]]'', portraying the life of a press magnate (played by Welles) who starts out as an [[idealism|idealist]] but eventually turns into a corrupt, lonely old man. The film featured Cotten prominently in the role of Kane's best friend [[Sources for Citizen Kane#Jedediah Leland|Jedediah Leland]], eventually a drama critic for one of Kane's papers.\n\nWhen released on May 1, 1941, ''Citizen Kane'' \u2014 based in part on the life of [[William Randolph Hearst]] \u2014 did not do much business at theaters; Hearst owned numerous major newspapers, and forbade them to carry advertisements for the film. Nominated for nine [[Academy Awards]] in 1942, the film won only for Best Screenplay, for Mankiewicz and Welles. ''Citizen Kane'' launched the film careers of the Mercury Players, including [[Agnes Moorehead]] (who played Kane's mother), [[Ruth Warrick]] (Kane's first wife), and [[Ray Collins (actor)|Ray Collins]] (Kane's political opponent). However, Cotten was the only one of the four to find major success as a lead in Hollywood outside of ''Citizen Kane''; Moorehead and Collins became successful character film actors and Warrick spent decades in a career in daytime television.\n\n[[Alexander Korda]] then hired Cotten to play [[Merle Oberon]]'s leading man in ''[[Lydia (film)|Lydia]]'' (1941). \"I didn't care about the movies, really,\" Cotten said later. \"I was tall. I had curly hair. I could talk. It was easy to do.\"<ref name=\"los\"/>\n\n===''The Magnificent Ambersons'' and ''Journey Into Fear''===\nCotten starred in Welles's adaptation and production of ''[[The Magnificent Ambersons (film)|The Magnificent Ambersons]]'' (1942). After the commercial disappointment of ''Citizen Kane'', RKO was apprehensive about the new film, and after poor preview responses, cut it by nearly an hour before its release. Though at points the film appeared disjointed, it was well received by critics. Despite the critical accolades Cotten received for his performance, he was again snubbed by the Academy.\n\nCotten was cast in the [[Nazism|Nazi]]-related thriller ''[[Journey into Fear (1943 film)|Journey into Fear]]'' (1943) based on the novel by [[Eric Ambler]]. It was originally scripted by [[Ben Hecht]] but Welles, who was supervising, disliked it, and he rewrote it with Cotten.<ref>{{cite news| title= Welles Actor Teamed With Michele Morgan: John Carroll Borrowed New ...| last= Schallert| first= Edwin | work= Los Angeles Times | date= April 26, 1941| page= A9}}</ref> Released by RKO, the Mercury production was directed by [[Norman Foster (director)|Norman Foster]]. It was a collaborative effort due to the difficulties shooting the film and the pressures related to Welles's imminent departure to South America to begin work on ''[[It's All True (film)|It's All True]]''.<ref name=\"TIOW\">{{cite book| last1= Welles| first1= Orson| first2= Peter |last2= Bogdanovich| editor= [[Jonathan Rosenbaum]]| title= [[This is Orson Welles]]| place= New York| publisher= [[HarperCollins]] | year= 1992 | isbn= 0-06-016616-9}}</ref>{{Rp|165, 377}}<ref>{{cite news| title= Screen News Here and in Hollywood: MGM May Lend Wallace Beery to ... | first= Douglas W. | last= Churchill| work= The New York Times | date= July 29, 1941| page= 19}}</ref>\n\n[[Alfred Hitchcock]] hired Cotten to play a charming serial killer in ''[[Shadow of a Doubt]]'' (1943). It was made for Universal Pictures, who for whom Cotten then appeared in ''[[Hers to Hold]]'' (1943), as [[Deanna Durbin]]'s leading man.\n\nAfter Welles's return he and Cotten co-produced ''[[The Mercury Wonder Show]]'' for members of the U.S. armed services. Opening August 3, 1943, the all-star magic and variety show was presented in a tent at 9000 Cahuenga Boulevard in Hollywood. Featured were Welles (Orson the Magnificent), Cotten (Jo-Jo the Great), [[Rita Hayworth]] (forced to quit by [[Columbia Pictures]] boss [[Harry Cohn]] and replaced by [[Marlene Dietrich]]), [[Agnes Moorehead]] (Calliope Aggie) and others. Tickets were free to servicemen, and more than 48,000 of them had seen show by September 1943.<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|177, 377\u2013378}}\n\n===David O. Selznick===\nIn late 1943, Cotten visited Welles's office and said that producer [[David O. Selznick]] wanted to make two or three films with him, but that he wanted him under his own contract. Welles then tore up Cotten's contract with Mercury Productions, saying, \"He can do more for you than I can. Good luck!\"<ref name=\"Whaley\">[http://www.lybrary.com/barton-whaley-m-191.html Whaley, Barton], ''Orson Welles: The Man Who Was Magic''. Lybrary.com, 2005,</ref>{{Rp|186}} Cotten signed a long term deal with Selznick.\n\nSelznick loaned out Cotten and [[Ingrid Bergman]] to [[MGM]] for the thriller ''[[Gaslight (1944 film)|Gaslight]]'' (1944) which was a major hit. Selznick then put Cotten in a wartime drama ''[[Since You Went Away]]'' (1944) alongside [[Claudette Colbert]], [[Jennifer Jones]] and [[Shirley Temple]]; it was another major success.<ref name=\"tom\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=dwf5SUcfousC&pg=PA190 Thomas Schatz, ''Boom and Bust: American Cinema in the 1940s'' University of California Press, 1999. p. 190] accessed 1 Jan 2014</ref>\n\nSelznick followed this up by teaming Cotten with [[Ginger Rogers]] and Temple in ''[[I'll Be Seeing You (1944 film)|I'll Be Seeing You]]'' (1945), another melodrama. [[Hal Wallis]] borrowed Cotten and Jones to make ''[[Love Letters (1945 film)|Love Letters]]'' (1945). Exhibitors voted him the 17th most popular star in the United States in 1945.<ref>\"Bing Crosby Again Box-Office Leader:  Van Johnson Second in Film Poll of Exhibitors{{spaced ndash}} Rogers Wins for Westerns\".  ''[[The New York Times]]''.  December 28, 1945.  p. 21.</ref>\n\nSelznick used Cotten, Jennifer Jones and [[Gregory Peck]] in ''[[Duel in the Sun (film)|Duel in the Sun]]'' (1946), an epic Western that was hugely popular at the box office.\n\n[[Dore Schary]], who had worked for Selznick, went to run RKO and hired Cotten for ''[[The Farmer's Daughter (1947 film)|The Farmer's Daughter]]'' (1947), where he was [[Loretta Young]]'s leading man. Cotten then made ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]'' (1948) for Selznick, co starring with Jones; Cotten played a melancholy artist who becomes obsessed with a girl who might have died many years before. His performance won Cotten the International Prize for Best Actor at the 1949 Venice International Film Festival.<ref>Joseph Cotten;Obituary\nThe Times; London (UK) [London (UK)]08 Feb 1994.</ref>\n\n===''The Third Man''===\nCotten was reunited with Welles in ''[[The Third Man]]'' (1949), produced by Korda and Selznick. Cotten portrays a writer of [[pulp magazine|pulp fiction]] who travels to postwar [[Vienna]] to meet his friend Harry Lime (Welles). When he arrives, he is told that Lime has died. Determined to prove to the police that his friend was murdered, he uncovers an even darker secret.\n\n(Welles and Cotten remained close friends until Welles's death in 1985. According to Welles, Cotten was always uncomfortable as a leading man and preferred to play supporting or [[character actor|character]] roles.<ref name=Biskind>{{cite book| editor-first= Peter |editor-last= Biskind | title= My Lunches with Orson: Conversations Between Henry Jaglom and Orson Welles| publisher= Macmillan | year= 2013}}</ref>)\n\nCotten then reunited with Hitchcock and Ingrid Bergman in ''[[Under Capricorn]]'' (1949) as an Australian landowner with a shady past; it was a box office disappointment. So too was ''[[Beyond the Forest]]'' (1949) with [[Bette Davis]] at Warner Bros.<ref>SELZNICK STARS TO DO MOVIES FOR WARNERS\nSpecial to THE NEW YORK TIMES.. New York Times 21 Feb 1949: 18.</ref><ref>NEWS OF THE SCREEN\nBy THOMAS F. BRADYS New York Times 22 June 1948: 22.</ref>\n\nCotten co-starred with [[Joan Fontaine]] in ''[[September Affair]]'' (1950) for Hal Wallis. Selznick loaned him to 20th Century Fox for the dark [[American Civil War|Civil War]] Western ''[[Two Flags West]]'' (1950), then to RKO for ''[[Walk Softly, Stranger]]'' (1950, shot in 1948) which reunited him with [[Alida Valli]] from ''The Third Man''. It was a huge flop.<ref name=\"rko\">Jewell, Richard and Vernon Harbin, ''The RKO Story.'' New Rochelle, New York: Arlington House, 1982, p. 253.</ref>\n\nAt Fox he did ''[[Half Angel (film)|Half Angel]]'' (1951) with Young, then did another with Wallis at Paramount, ''[[Peking Express (film)|Peking Express]]'' (1951) and went to MGM for ''[[The Man with a Cloak]]'' (1951) with [[Barbara Stanwyck]]. He had a cameo in Welles' ''[[Othello (1951 film)|Othello]]'' (1951).<ref>METRO FILM LEAD TO JOSEPH COTTEN: Studio Signs Actor for Role in 'Man With the Cloak'-- Markie Directing Movie Of Local Origin\nBy THOMAS F. BRADY New York Times 20 Feb 1951: 21.</ref>\n\nCotten did a Western at Universal, ''[[Untamed Frontier]]'' (1953), during the filming of which he was injured.<ref>Joseph Cotten, Injured on Set, Returns to L.A.\nLos Angeles Times 21 Dec 1951: A1.</ref> He did a thriller for [[Andrew L. Stone]], ''[[The Steel Trap]]'' (1952), which reunited with Teresa Wright from ''Shadow of a Doubt''.<ref>SCANNING COTTEN'S TERRITORY\nBy HOWARD THOMPSON. New York Times 23 Nov 1952: X4.</ref>\n\nAt Fox he was in the [[Marilyn Monroe]] vehicle ''[[Niagara (1953 film)|Niagara]]'' (1953), after [[James Mason]] turned down the role. He narrated ''[[Egypt by Three]]'' (1953) and was reunited with Stone in ''[[A Blueprint for Murder]]'' (1953).\n\n===''Sabrina Fair'' and television===\nOn the stage in 1953, Cotten created the role of Linus Larrabee, Jr., in the original Broadway production of ''[[Sabrina Fair]]'', opposite [[Margaret Sullavan]]. The production ran November 11, 1953 \u2013 August 21, 1954, and was the basis of the [[Billy Wilder]] film ''[[Sabrina (1954 film)|Sabrina]]'', which starred [[Humphrey Bogart]] and [[Audrey Hepburn]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibdb.com/production.php?id=2387 |title=Sabrina Fair |website= ibdb.com |publisher= Internet Broadway Database |accessdate=2014-03-25}}</ref> He and Sullivan did a TV production of ''[[State of the Union (play)|State of the Union]]'' for ''[[Producers' Showcase]]'' directed by [[Arthur Penn]].\n\nCotten made ''[[Special Delivery (1955 film)|Special Delivery]]'' (1955) in West Germany, did a TV adaptation of ''[[Broadway (play)|Broadway]]'' for ''[[The Best of Broadway]]'' (1955) directed by [[Franklin J. Schaffner]]. He appeared in episodes of ''[[Celebrity Playhouse]]'', ''[[The Ford Television Theatre]]'', ''[[Star Stage]]'', ''[[Alfred Hitchcock Presents]]'' (several times) and ''[[General Electric Theater]]''.<ref>Joseph Cotten Arrives in Germany for Role\nLos Angeles Times 18 Nov 1954: 21.</ref>\n\nIn 1955 Cotten hosted ''The 20th Century Fox Hour'' on television.<ref name=\"joe\"/>\n\nIn 1956, Cotten starred in the [[NBC]] anthology series ''On Trial''<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Becker|first1=Christine|title=Televising Film Stardom in the 1950s|journal=Framework|url-access=subscription  |via=[[Questia Online Library]]|date=October 1, 2005|url=https://www.questia.com/read/1P3-1001342431|accessdate=21 January 2015}}</ref> (renamed at mid-season ''[[The Joseph Cotten Show]]''). It ran for 41 episodes.<ref name=\"joe\">Joseph Cotten's Toughest TV Role Is Playing a Guy Named Joseph Cotten\nThomas, Bob. Chicago Daily Tribune 19 May 1956: d5.</ref>\n\nHe returned to features with ''[[The Bottom of the Bottle]]'' (1956), ''[[The Killer Is Loose]]'' (1957) and ''[[The Halliday Brand]]'' (1957).\n\nHe guest starred on ''[[Jane Wyman Presents The Fireside Theatre]]'', ''[[Telephone Time]]'', ''[[Playhouse 90]]'', ''[[Schlitz Playhouse]]'', ''[[Zane Grey Theater]]'', ''[[Suspicion (TV series)|Suspicion]]'', and ''[[Westinghouse Desilu Playhouse]]''. He made a [[cameo role|cameo]] appearance in Welles's''[[Touch of Evil]]'' (1958) and a starring role in the film adaptation of [[Jules Verne]]'s ''[[From the Earth to the Moon (film)|From the Earth to the Moon]]'' (also 1958).\n\nCotten had another success on Broadway when he appeared in ''[[Once More, with Feeling!|Once More, With Feeling]]'' (1958\u201360) which ran for 263 performances.<ref>Joseph Cotten Stars With Arlene Francis: 'Once More, With Feeling'\nBy Edwin F. Melvin. The Christian Science Monitor8 Oct 1958: 7.</ref> For the third time Cotten was in a Broadway hit but did not reprise his role in the film version \u2013 [[Yul Brynner]] did.\n\n===1960s===\n[[File:Joseph Cotten & Patricia Medina Allan Warren.jpg|thumb|right|Cotten and Patricia Medina in 1973]]\nIn 1960, Cotten married British actress [[Patricia Medina]] after his first wife, Lenore Kipp, died of [[leukemia]] earlier in the year.<ref name=\"NYT Obit\"/><ref>Joseph Cotten and Patricia Medina to Wed Hopper, Hedda. Los Angeles Times 8 Oct 1960: 4.</ref>\n\nCotten had a supporting role in the films ''[[The Angel Wore Red]]'' (1960) and ''[[The Last Sunset (film)|The Last Sunset]]'' (1961), the latter directed by [[Robert Aldrich]], and guest starred on ''[[The DuPont Show with June Allyson]]'', ''[[Checkmate (TV series)|Checkmate]]'', ''[[The Barbara Stanwyck Show]]'', ''[[Bus Stop (TV series)|Bus Stop]]'', ''[[Theatre '62]]'' (an adaptation of ''[[Notorious (1946 film)|Notorious]]''), ''[[Dr. Kildare (TV series)|Dr. Kildare]]'', ''[[Wagon Train]]'', and ''[[Saints and Sinners (1962 TV series)|Saints and Sinners]]''.\n\nCotten returned to Broadway to appear in ''Calculated Risk'' (1962\u201363), which ran for 221 performances and meant he had to turn down a role in a film ''Harrigan's Halo''.<ref>Films, Stage Joust Over Joseph Cotten: Star Plans to Divide Time; Kruger Sets 'Lion and Lamb'\nScott, John L. Los Angeles Times (1923\u20131995); Los Angeles, Calif. [Los Angeles, Calif]06 July 1962: C9.</ref><ref>https://www.ibdb.com/broadway-production/calculated-risk-2928</ref> He guest starred on ''[[The Great Adventure (U.S. TV series)|The Great Adventure]]'', and ''[[77 Sunset Strip]]'', and did the pilot ''[[Alexander the Great (TV movie)|Alexander the Great]]'' (1963).<ref>Joseph Cotten Starring\nThe Christian Science Monitor 20 June 1962: 6.</ref>\n\nAfter some time away from film, Cotten returned in the [[horror films|horror]] classic ''[[Hush\u2026 Hush, Sweet Charlotte]]'' (1964) for Aldrich, with [[Bette Davis]], [[Olivia de Havilland]] and [[Agnes Moorehead]].\n\n===Final leading man roles===\nCotten was top billed in ''[[The Great Sioux Massacre]]'' (1965) and ''[[The Tramplers]]'' (1965), but back to support parts for ''[[The Money Trap]]'' (1965) and ''[[The Oscar (film)|The Oscar]]'' (1966). He was top billed in ''[[Brighty of the Grand Canyon]]'' (1966), directed by Foster, ''[[The Cruel Ones]]'' (1967), ''[[Some May Live]]'' (1967) and ''[[Gangsters '70]]'' (1968).<ref>Joseph Cotten\u2014He'll Gladly Meet Fame and Fortune Half Way\nAlpert, Don. Los Angeles Times 13 June 1965: n4.</ref>\n\nHe guest starred on ''[[Cimarron Strip]]'', ''[[Ironside (TV series)|Ironside]]'', and ''[[Journey to the Unknown]]'' and had a support role in ''[[Jack of Diamonds (1967 film)|Jack of Diamonds]]'' (1967). He had the lead in ''[[White Comanche]]'' (1968) and ''[[Latitude Zero (film)|Latitude Zero]]'' (1969) (shot in Japan with his wife) and supported in the TV movies ''[[The Lonely Profession]]'' (1969), ''[[Cutter's Trail]]'' (1970).<ref>TV Today:: Joseph Cotten's Feet Aren't Clay\nKramer, Carol. Chicago Tribune 13 Oct 1969: c15.</ref>\n\n===1970s===\nCotten was in ''[[The Name of the Game (TV series)|The Name of the Game]]'', ''It Takes a Thief'', ''[[NET Playhouse]]'', ''[[The Grasshopper (1970 film)|The Grasshopper]]'' (1970), ''[[Tora! Tora! Tora!]]'', ''The Virginian'', ''[[Assault on the Wayne]]'' (1971), ''[[Do You Take This Stranger?]]'' (1971), ''[[City Beneath the Sea (1971 film)|City Beneath the Sea]]'' (1971), ''[[The Abominable Dr. Phibes]]'' (1971), ''[[Lady Frankenstein]]'' (1971), and ''[[The Screaming Woman]]'' (1972) with de Havilland.<ref>Joseph Cotten: His Accent's on Acting\nLos Angeles Times 18 July 1968: f16.</ref>\n\nHe had lead roles in ''[[Doomsday Voyage]]'' (1972), ''[[Baron Blood (film)|Baron Blood]]'' (1972), and ''[[The Scopone Game]]'' (1973) and was in ''[[The Devil's Daughter (1973 film)|The Devil's Daughter]]'' (1973),<ref>Joseph Cotten signs\nLos Angeles Times 20 Oct 1972: d26.</ref> ''[[The Streets of San Francisco]]'', ''[[Soylent Green]]'' (1973), ''[[A Delicate Balance (film)|A Delicate Balance]]'' (1973), ''[[The Rockford Files]]'', ''[[Syndicate Sadists]]'' (1975), ''[[The Timber Tramps]]'' (1975), ''[[The Lindbergh Kidnapping Case]]'' (1976), ''[[A Whisper in the Dark]]'' (1976), ''[[Origins of the Mafia]]'' (1976), ''[[Twilight's Last Gleaming]]'' (1977) for Aldrich, ''[[Airport '77]]'', ''[[Aspen (miniseries)|Aspen]]'' (1977), ''[[The Hardy Boys/Nancy Drew Mysteries]]'', ''[[Last In, First Out]]'' (1978), ''[[Caravans (film)|Caravans]]'' (1978), ''[[Indagine su un delitto perfetto]]'' (1978), ''[[Screamers (1979 film)|Screamers]]'' (1979), ''[[Concorde Affaire '79]]'' (1979), ''[[Guyana: Cult of the Damned]]'' (1979), ''[[Churchill and the Generals]]'' (1979), ''[[Tales of the Unexpected (TV series)|Tales of the Unexpected]]'' and ''[[Fantasy Island]]''.<ref>Joseph Cotten to Guest in Hardy Boys\nLos Angeles Times 31 Mar 1978: g19.</ref><ref>Joseph Cotten Cast as Coin Collector\nLos Angeles Times2 Oct 1972: d20.</ref>\n\n\"I was in a lot of junk,\" he admitted later. \"I get nervous when I don't work.\"<ref name=\"vanity\"/>\n\n===Final roles===\nCotten's final performances included ''[[The Hearse (film)|The Hearse]]'' (1980), ''[[Casino (TV movie)|Casino]]'' (1980), ''[[Heaven's Gate (film)|Heaven's Gate]]'' (1980), ''[[The Love Boat]]'' (1981), ''[[The Survivor (1981 film)|The Survivor]]'' (1981), shot in Australia, and ''[[Delusion (1981 film)|Delusion]]'' (1981). Cotten suffered a stroke in 1981 which caused him to temporarily lose his voice.<ref>[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1291&dat=19850721&id=ZCdUAAAAIBAJ&sjid=IY0DAAAAIBAJ&pg=1141,5715318 Actor winning battle against stroke]</ref>\n\n==Illness and death==\nOn June 8, 1981, Cotten experienced a [[heart attack]] followed by a [[stroke]] that affected his [[Language processing in the brain|brain's speech center]]. He began years of therapy which in time made it possible for him to speak again. As he began to recover, he and Orson Welles talked on the phone each week for a couple of hours. \"He was strong and supportive,\" Cotten wrote, \"and whenever I used the wrong word (which was frequently) he would say, 'That's a much better word, Jo, I'm going to use it.'\" He and Welles would meet for lunch and reminisce. When Cotten announced he had written a book, Welles asked for the manuscript and read it that night.<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|215\u2013217|date=March 2014}}\n\nIn a phone conversation on October 9, 1985, Welles told his friend and mentor Roger Hill that Cotten had written a book, and Hill asked how it read. \"Gentle, witty, and self-effacing, just like Jo,\" Welles replied. \"My only complaint is that it's too brief.\"<ref name=\"Tarbox\">{{cite book |last=Tarbox |first= Todd |date=2013 |title=Orson Welles and Roger Hill: A Friendship in Three Acts |location=Albany, Georgia |publisher=BearManor Media |page=289 |isbn=1-59393-260-X}}</ref> Welles died the following day. \"Somewhere among his possessions is a manuscript of this book,\" Cotten wrote on the last page of his autobiography, published in 1987 under the title ''Vanity Will Get You Somewhere''.<ref name=\"Vanity\"/>{{Rp|217|date=March 2014}}<ref>{{cite web| url= https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1817&dat=19870607&id=BjYdAAAAIBAJ&sjid=q6UEAAAAIBAJ&pg=5793,1443378 |title='Citizen Kane' star releases witty, irreverent autobiography  |work= The Tuscaloosa News| page= 13C| agency= Associated Press| date= June 7, 1987 |accessdate= 2014-03-25}}</ref><ref name=\"vanity\">Joseph Cotten, on the High Road: Fighting Back From a Stroke, the Actor Promotes a Gentle Memoir Actor Joseph Cotten\nBy Stephanie Mansfield Washington Post Staff Writer. The Washington Post 17 June 1987: B1.</ref>\n\nIn 1990, Cotten's [[larynx]] was removed due to [[cancer]].<ref name=\"LA Times\">{{cite news| url=http://articles.latimes.com/1994-02-07/news/mn-20181_1_joseph-cotten | work= [[Los Angeles Times]] | title=Debonair Actor Joseph Cotten Dies at 88| first=Myrna | last=Oliver | date=February 7, 1994 | accessdate=2014-03-09}}</ref> He died on February 6, 1994, of [[pneumonia]], at the age of 88.<ref name=\"NYT Obit\">{{cite news| url=https://query.nytimes.com/gst/fullpage.html?res=9402E1DA1638F934A35751C0A962958260 | work= [[The New York Times]] | title=Joseph Cotten, 88, Is Dead; Actor on Stage and in Films | first=Peter B. | last=Flint | date=February 7, 1994 | accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He was buried at [[Blandford Cemetery]] in [[Petersburg, Virginia|Petersburg]], [[Virginia]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.waymarking.com/waymarks/WMAT42_Joseph_Cotten_Petersburg_Virginia |title= Joseph Cotten \u2013 Petersburg, Virginia| website= waymarking.com}}</ref>\n\n==Accolades==\nAt the [[10th Venice International Film Festival]], Cotten was given the [[Volpi Cup for Best Actor]] for his performance in the film ''[[Portrait of Jennie]]'' (1948). He was also given a star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in 1960.\n\n==Cultural references==\nCotten was portrayed by [[Tim Robbins]] in the 1985 TV film ''[[Malice in Wonderland (1985 film)|Malice in Wonderland]]'', [[James Tupper]] in the film ''[[Me and Orson Welles]]'' (2008)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2008/film/markets-festivals/me-and-orson-welles-1200470866/|title=Film Review: Me and Orson Welles |last=McCarthy |first=Todd |authorlink=Todd McCarthy |date=September 6, 2008 |website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |access-date=2015-09-07}}</ref> and by [[Matthew Glave]] in the television series ''[[Feud (TV series)|Feud]]'' (2017), which depicts the filming of ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (1962 film)|Whatever Happened to Baby Jane]]''.\n\n==Theatre credits==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Date\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| October 17, 1932 \u2013 January 1933\n| ''Absent Father''\n| Larry\n| [[Vanderbilt Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"Cotten IBDb\">{{cite web |url=http://ibdb.com/Person/View/36425 |title=Joseph Cotten |last1= |first1= |last2= |first2= |date= |website= |publisher=[[Internet Broadway Database]] |access-date=2015-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 19, 1933 \u2013 January 1934\n| ''Jezebel''\n| Dick Ashley\n| [[Ethel Barrymore Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"Cotten IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| February 4 \u2013 February 1934\n| ''Loose Moments''\n| Ralph Merkes\n| Vanderbilt Theatre, New York<ref name=\"Cotten IBDb\"/>\n|-\n| September 26 \u2013 December 5, 1936\n| ''[[Horse Eats Hat]]''\n| Freddy\n| [[Maxine Elliott Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|334}}\n|-\n| January 8 \u2013 April 1, 1937\n| ''[[Doctor Faustus (play)|Faustus]]''\n| 2nd Scholar\n| Maxine Elliott Theatre, New York<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|335\u2013336}}\n|-\n| April 21\u201323, 1937\n| ''[[The Second Hurricane]]''\n| Airplane pilot<ref name=\"Anderson\">{{cite book |last=Anderson |first=Arthur |authorlink=Arthur Anderson (voice actor) |date=2010 |title=An Actor's Odyssey |location=Albany, Georgia |publisher=BearManor Media |isbn=9781593935221 |url=https://archive.org/details/actorsodysseyfro00ande }}</ref>{{Rp|33}}\n| [[Henry Street Settlement]], New York City<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|337}}\n|-\n| November 11, 1937 \u2013 May 28, 1938\n| ''[[Caesar (Mercury Theatre)|Caesar]]''\n| [[Servilius Casca|Publius]]\n| [[Comedy Theatre (New York City)|Mercury Theatre]], New York<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|339\u2013340}}<br>Moved to the larger [[Nederlander Theatre|National Theatre]] January 24, 1938<ref name=\"TIOW\"/>{{Rp|341}}<ref>{{cite news |last= |first= |date=May 28, 1938 |title=News of the Stage; 'Julius Caesar' Closes Tonight |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1938/05/28/archives/news-of-the-stage-julius-caesar-closes-tonightthe-two-bouquets-only.html |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=2015-11-07}}</ref>\n|-\n| December 25, 1937\n| ''The Shoemaker's Holiday''\n| Rowland Lacy\n| Mercury Theatre, New York<br>Surprise preview performance immediately following ''Caesar''<ref name=\"Houseman RT\">{{cite book |last=Houseman |first=John |authorlink=John Houseman |title=Run-Through: A Memoir |url=https://archive.org/details/runthroughmemoir00hous |url-ac