{"title_page": "\u014cuda, Nara", "text_new": "{{Infobox city Japan\n|name               = \u014cuda\n|native_name        = \u5927\u5b87\u9640\u753a\n|settlement_type    = Former municipality\n|image_skyline      = Ouda_street.jpg\n|image_caption      = The main street in \u014cuda\n|image_map          = \n|region             = [[Kansai region|Kansai]] ([[Kinki region|Kinki]])\n|prefecture         = [[Nara Prefecture]]\n|district           = [[Uda District, Nara|Uda]]\n|merged             = January 1, 2006\n|merged_into        = [[Uda, Nara|Uda]]\n|area_km2           = 47.44\n|population_as_of   = 2005\n|population         = 8,647\n|density_km2        = auto\n|coordinates        = {{coord|34|28|44.2|N|135|55|41.1|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n|tree               = Oak\n|flower             = Pinwheel\n|bird               = Bunting\n|website            = [http://www.city.uda.nara.jp/ City of Uda]\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''\u014cuda'''|\u5927\u5b87\u9640\u753a|\u014cuda-ch\u014d}} was a [[List of towns in Japan|town]] located in [[Uda District, Nara|Uda District]], [[Nara Prefecture]], [[Japan]].\n\nAs of 2005, the town had an estimated [[population]] of 8,647 and a [[population density|density]] of 182.27 persons per km\u00b2. The total area was 47.44&nbsp;km\u00b2.\n\nOn January 1, 2006, \u014cuda, along with the towns of [[Haibara, Nara|Haibara]] and [[Utano, Nara|Utano]] (all from [[Uda District, Nara|Uda District]]), was merged to create the city of [[Uda, Nara|Uda]].\n\nThe town of \u014cuda lies in a valley between two long mountain ranges in northeastern [[Nara Prefecture|Nara]], [[Japan]]. A three-mile long stretch of national routes 166 and 370 in the southern part of the town is where most of the businesses and homes are clustered. A large portion of flat land north on route 370 is less densely populated, covered mostly by rice fields. A large ''[[torii]]'', or Japanese Gate, rises out of the rice paddies.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Ouda.jpg|\nFile:Ouda_outskirts.jpg|The outskirts of \u014cuda\n</gallery>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouda, Nara}}\n[[Category:Dissolved municipalities of Nara Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in Japan]]\n{{Nara-geo-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox city Japan\n|name               = \u014cuda\n|native_name        = \u5927\u5b87\u9640\u753a\n|settlement_type    = Former municipality\n|image_skyline      = Ouda_street.jpg\n|image_caption      = The main street in \u014cuda\n|image_map          = \n|region             = [[Kansai region|Kansai]] ([[Kinki region|Kinki]])\n|prefecture         = [[Nara Prefecture]]\n|district           = [[Uda District, Nara|Uda]]\n|merged             = January 1, 2006\n|merged_into        = [[Uda, Nara|Uda]]\n|area_km2           = 47.44\n|population_as_of   = 2005\n|population         = 8,647\n|density_km2        = auto\n|coordinates        = {{coord|34|28|44.2|N|135|55|41.1|E|region:JP|display=inline,title}}\n|tree               = Oak\n|flower             = Pinwheel\n|bird               = Bunting\n|website            = [http://www.city.uda.nara.jp/ City of Uda]\n|footnotes          = \n}}\n\n{{nihongo|'''\u014cuda'''|\u5927\u5b87\u9640\u753a|\u014cuda-ch\u014d}} was a [[List of towns in Japan|town]] located in [[Uda District, Nara|Uda District]], [[Nara Prefecture]], [[Japan]].\n\nAs of 2005, the town had an estimated [[population]] of 8,647 and a [[population density|density]] of 182.27 persons per km\u00b2. The total area was 47.44&nbsp;km\u00b2.\n\nOn January 1, 2006, \u014cuda, along with the towns of [[Haibara, Nara|Haibara]] and [[Utano, Nara|Utano]] (all from [[Uda District, Nara|Uda District]]), was merged to create the city of [[Uda, Nara|Uda]].\n\nThe town of \u014cuda lies in a valley between two long mountain ranges in northeastern [[Nara Prefecture|Nara]], [[Japan]]. A three-mile long stretch of national routes 166 and 370 in the southern part of the town is where most of the businesses and homes are clustered. A large portion of flat land north on route 370 is less densely populated, covered mostly by rice fields. A large ''[[torii]]'', or Japanese Gate, rises out of the rice paddies.\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Ouda.jpg|\nFile:Ouda_outskirts.jpg|The outskirts of \u014cuda\n</gallery>\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Ouda, Nara}}\n[[Category:Dissolved municipalities of Nara Prefecture]]\n[[Category:Populated places disestablished in 2006]]\n[[Category:2000s disestablishments in Japan]]\n[[Category:2006 disestablishments in Japan]]\n{{Nara-geo-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "Removing fromCategory:2000s disestablishments in JapanusingCat-a-lot", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C5%8Cuda,_Nara"}
